<FIRST>u a AM-RejectedRefugees     04-22 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rejected Refugees,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifth Chartered Flight Departs South Padre Island For Central America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 120 refugees was put on a
jetliner and returned to El Salvador in the latest mass deportation
of illegal aliens by the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
   The flight of the INS-chartered Boeing 737 was the fifth such
flight since Feb. 21, when the INS began a crackdown on
undocumented aliens crossing the Rio Grande.
   A previous charter flight of 231 aliens left Texas on March 13
and was believed to be the largest mass deportation by the INS.
More than 1,300 Central Americans have been deported since the
crackdown began.
   The refugees _ some smiling, other sulking _ were processed out
of the INS detention camp near Bayview and filed into four buses
bound for the Brownsville-South Padre Island International Airport.
   There were no Nicaraguans on the flight, although more than a
quarter of the 1,250 detainees at the camp are from Nicaragua.
   Nicaraguans are the only nationality to have escaped the
crackdown, thanks to a directive issued by then-Attorney General
Edwin Meese III, in July 1987.
   Meese requested that the INS encourage asylum applications and
work authorizations for refugees fleeing the leftist Nicaraguan
government. Deportation for Nicaraguans must be approved by INS
headquarters in Washington, D.C.
   Among the immigrants deported Thursday were 68 Salvadorans, 38
Guatemalans and 14 Hondurans.
   The INS said 703 refugees applied for asylum in the Harlingen
district since Feb. 21. Of those applicants, 72 Nicaraguans and six
Salvadorans were granted asylum. The rest were detained to be sent
back to their homelands.
</TEXT>
