<FIRST>r w PM-Lebanon-Demonstration     04-22 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Demonstration,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Seek US Help to End Fighting in Their Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States must pressure Syria to stop
the shelling that has killed hundreds in Beirut and made life for
the survivors virtually unlivable, according to 2,000 Lebanese who
demonstrated across from the White House.
   ``It's a total breakdown of everything,'' said May Rihani, a
Washington D.C. consultant who visited her family in Beirut in
September. ``No work, no school, no electricity.''
   ``It's unbearable, unpredictable, unlivable'' since Syrian
forces began bombarding Beirut's Christian enclave in early March,
said Samuel Ibrahim, a Lebanese-born Chicago businessman who also
has relatives living there. ``It's inhumane to shell ... peaceful,
innocent people,'' he said.
   The demonstrators came to Washington on Friday from across the
United States and Canada, and were organized by a variety of
pro-Lebanese groups.
   Marching in Lafayette Park across the street from the White
House, they carried signs and sang the Lebanese national anthem
amid chants of ``President Bush, Save Lebanon.''
   The International Movement for the Liberation of Lebanon, an
organizer of the demonstration, said in a letter to Bush it was
disappointed by a statement by Secretary of State James A. Baker
earlier this week that the United States can do little at present
to help Lebanon.
   Bush told reporters Thursday he wished there were ``some
dramatic plan'' to stop the violence. ``The problem _ the short-run
of it _ how you stop this firing, the shelling, how you get
factions to stop warring, has certainly in recent times defied
solution,'' Bush said. ``But we can't give up on it.''
   Several demonstrators suggested the United States could use
diplomatic or economic pressure in an effort to force Syria to
withdraw its 40,000 troops from their country.
   At least 270 people, mainly civilians, have been killed and
nearly 1,000 wounded in shelling since March 8. More than 150,000
Christians and Moslems have fled Beirut out of fear of fighting or
due to shortages of food and fuel.
   Elia Sarkis, a Boston businessman who brought his 11-year-old
son to the demonstration, said he believes that if Syria withdrew,
the warring Lebanese religious and ethnic factions would find a way
to form a workable government.
   ``A federation of religious, ethnic communities ... that's the
ideal new Lebanon that we're looking for,'' Sarkis said.
</TEXT>
