<NOTE>Bush Gives Medal to Philanthropist</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush awarded the congressional medal
to philanthropist Mary Lasker, honoring her for longtime support of
research and education in such areas as cancer, heart disease and
cerebral palsy.
   Bush, in a Rose Garden presentation ceremony on Friday, told
Mrs. Lasker she was an example of what he means when he speaks of
``1,000 points of light'' as the many components of society that
work to improve life for everyone.
   Mrs. Lasker and her husband in 1942 founded the Albert and Mary
Lasker Foundation to encourage medical research and public
awareness of crippling diseases.
   She urged the president to beef up support for the National
Institutes of Health, where the Mary W. Lasker Center for Health
Research and Education conducts medical research. ``Cancer still
kills 500,000 people a year in this country, more people than have
been killed in all our wars combined,'' she said.
