<NOTE>Donovan Wants Government to Pay Legal Bills</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Labor Secretary Raymond Donovan is
asking an appeals court panel to order the federal government to
pay $112,281 in legal bills he says he incurred during an
investigation of an alleged kickback supposedly paid Donovan in
1977.
   Donovan and his lawyers say the legal fees and expenses are for
the period March 1987 through October 1987 in connection with the
probe by independent counsel Leon Silverman.
   Federal law on independent counsels provides for the government
to pay legal fees if the subject of the criminal investigation
isn't indicted.
   Donovan was cleared in the probe of accusations that he lied
when he denied knowing anything about the alleged kickback scheme
which involved a former supplier of Schiavone Construction Co.
where Donovan was working at the time.
