<FIRST>u a AM-CentralPark 4thLd-Writethru a0408 04-22 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central Park, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0408,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Park after Dark: Safe or Scary?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Four teenagers ..., to UPDATE with further arrests,
doctor's statment that victim has a chance of full recovery.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rape and beating of a jogger has reinforced
the reputation of Central Park as a haven for criminals, which city
officials say is an unfair stereotype of America's most famous
urban park.
   ``Generally, crime in the park is low. It is safe to jog in
Central Park,'' said police Chief of Detectives Robert Colangelo
after the Wednesday night attack by a marauding gang of teen-agers
left a 28-year-old woman near death.
   ``There's danger in jogging anywhere,'' Colangelo said. ``But we
don't feel it's inordinately dangerous here.''
   The park's reputation for illegal activity has been reinforced
in recent years by several highly publicized incidents: Jennifer
Levin's 1986 strangling by ``preppie killer'' Robert Chambers, a
shooting a month earlier that left a police officer, Steven
McDonald, paralyzed, and a 1983 free concert by Diana Ross that
drew packs of thieves.
   The victim of the latest attack, an investment banker, remained
unconscious on life-support systems Friday at Metropolitan
Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Aura Retamoso.
   The woman lost roughly three-quarters of her body's blood in the
attack, and suffered a fractured skull, severe head lacerations,
brain contusions, fractured facial bones and bruises from head to
toe in the assault by a dozen teens, said Dr. Robert S. Kurtz,
assistant chief of surgery at the hospital.
   Kurtz said that on Friday her pulse rate ``went way up'' when
her mother spoke to her. ``So at some level she's processing
information today which she wasn't doing yesterday,'' he said.
   He said the next four days were crucial for her health, but
added ``she has a fighting chance of making a full recovery.''
   Seven teen-agers were arrested Friday and charged with attempted
murder, rape and assault in the attack. Police said additional
arrests were expected.
   Colangelo said the woman was attacked by some members of a group
of 32 teens who went to the park Wednesday night to ``raise hell,
attack joggers, steal bicycles.''
   Within 10 minutes, they had assaulted three men, including a
jogger and a homeless man. They later split up into three groups
after spotting a police cruiser and terrorized at least nine people
during a two-hour period.
   Colangelo said the youths told investigators the crime spree
resulted from a pastime called ``wilding.''
   ``It's not a term that we in the police had heard before,'' the
chief said. ``They just said, `We were going wilding.' In my mind
at this point, it implies that they were going to go raise hell.''
   ``Central Park is the focus of national attention. Every
incident that happens there is news _ especially if it's grisly,''
Parks Commissioner Henry Stern said Friday.
   Last year, police had reports of 51 assaults and 13 rapes in the
park, compared with 71,030 assaults and 3,412 rapes citywide.
   Of last year's attacks in the park, a dozen involved joggers; in
1987, 13 joggers were assaulted in the park. The rape Wednesday was
the third rape reported this year in Central Park, police said.
   Officials say the crime reports for the park are low for an area
larger than the country of Monaco. On a busy day, hundreds of
thousands of people pass through the park.
   Officials acknowledge the park has dangers after dark.
   ``It's safer to use it by day,'' Stern said. But he said,
``People shouldn't give up on the park any more than you would give
up on air travel because of a plane crash.''
   Fred Lebow, head of the New York Road Runners club, tells
evening joggers to avoid the northern area of the park, where the
Wednesday attack occurred. That area, bordering on Harlem, has more
rugged terrain and hiding places for criminals.
   Lebow's warning is based on history: One of his group's members
was raped in almost the same spot while jogging through the park
five years ago.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch also sounded a warning Friday about
jogging: ``If you do it in some parts of this town, you're
endangering your physical well-being, maybe occasionally even your
life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
