<FIRST>r a PM-StarkSailor     04-22 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stark Sailor,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailor Assails Compensation Plan For Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sailor injured when missiles ripped
into the USS Stark as it patrolled the Persian Gulf says the $7,500
the government is trying to get him as compensation is insulting.
   ``All this for $7,500?'' said Bill McLeod, who spent more than
11 hours in the gulf nursing his injuries and fighting off sharks
following the May 1987 attack.
   ``I'm starting to wonder was it all worth it,'' he said. ``It'd
be better off as far as compensation goes to go out and get in a
car wreck.''
   McLeod heard last month that the Iraqi government had agreed to
pay $27.35 million to the families of the 37 Navy sailors killed
aboard the Stark, and thought he would be compensated as one of the
22 sailors injured.
   McLeod received a letter from the State Department on Thursday
that said the United States would seek $7,500 for his injuries from
the Iraqis.
   The State Department would not comment on the total amount being
sought for the injured sailors.
   McLeod and the other sailors were injured when two Exocet
missiles fired by an Iraqi warplane hit the Stark in May 1987.
   He and three other sailors were thrown from the ship by the
blast.
   McLeod, who was awarded a Purple Heart, spent two weeks in a
wheelchair before returning to light duty.
   ``I think it's a ripoff. It's an insult,'' he said. McLeod and
his wife Rosa ``were thinking about $30,000 to $40,000 would be
about right.''
   The State Department letter invites McLeod to submit additional
information if he believes the claim is unjust.
   McLeod left the Navy after his enlistment expired in November
1987. The Navy paid his hospital bills plus $3,200 for personal
items lost on the ship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
