<HEAD>Government Releases Comedian, Actor After 7 Months In Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One name Zargana is correct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Burmese comedian and actor who satirized
the military shortly after it seized power have been released after
almost seven months imprisonment, authorities said today.
   The comedian, Zargana, and the actor, Zin Waing, were freed from
Insein Jail in Rangoon on Friday.
   Zargana, Zin Waing, and four other actors and directors were
arrested Oct. 2 but never publicly accused of any wrongdoing. The
others were freed earlier.
   Zargana said in a telephone interview today that he was kept in
solitary confinement but was not otherwise mistreated.
   ``The authorities explained to us yesterday why the military had
to step in on Sept. 18,'' Zargana said. ``We had to promise to
avoid acts that tend to cause misunderstanding between the army and
the public.''
   Armed forces commander Gen. Saw Maung seized power in a coup
that day against the country's first civilian president in 26
years. The general's troops killed hundreds of people in crushing
the nationwide street demonstrations for democracy.
