<FIRST>r a PM-FetusProject     04-22 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetus Project,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal Removes Jars Of Fetuses From Seventh-Grader's Exhibit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GATLINBURG, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school principal prevented a
seventh-grader from displaying her anti-abortion science project,
which consisted of 10 jars of human fetuses, saying the
award-winning exhibit was too much for his students.
   Carrie Walker placed the jars, which contained fetuses from
pregnancy stages ranging from 6 weeks to 5{ months, on her exhibit
table Thursday at Pi Beta Phi Elementary School, said Principal Al
Cardiel.
   ``To an untrained eye, the (fetus) 5{ months along was
definitely a child,'' said Jim Wade, curriculum director for Sevier
County schools.
   The girl said she got the fetuses, which were kept in
preservative solutions, from her uncle, a pathologist. The girl's
mother said the fetuses came from miscarriages.
   Cardiel said he learned of the exhibit early that morning as
students were setting up their projects for the school's annual
science fair, which this year has the theme ``Life Science.''
   ``The project was very inappropriate for the age group here,''
Cardiel said.
   He said he first conferred with Carrie's mother, Donna Walker,
who teaches art at the school. The project was removed from the
fair after it was graded and given a blue ribbon but before classes
had a chance to view it, said Sevier County School Superintendent
Jack Parton.
   Parton said he agreed with Cardiel that most of the
schoolchildren were too young to understand the ideas and points
behind the exhibit. Parton also said recent, nationwide political
debate over abortion played no part in the principal's decision to
yank the display from the fair.
   The school is located in Gatlinburg, an East Tennessee resort
town of about 3,000 people. About 430 students in kindergarten
through eighth grade attend the school.
</TEXT>
