<DOCNO> AP890422-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-22 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An honor roll student searching for a
way to protest his school's dress code found something his mother
would think natty _ a bright red pair of her culottes.
   ``They're saying we can't wear shorts, but girls can wear skirts
that are shorter than shorts, so they're indirectly discriminating
against guys,'' said Aaron Martinez, who was sent home Thursday
when he showed up in school sporting the outfit.
   On Friday, five other boys joined his protest by going to school
in skirts.
   School officials told them to change their clothing or go home.
Two went home, while the others changed to pants and went to class,
said principal Gary Blocker.
   The School Board's student dress policy clearly states that
culottes _ sometimes referred to as ``split skirts'' _ are
permissible. The policy does not say that only girls can wear
culottes to school.
   ``Culottes are for girls,'' Blocker said. ``The handbook doesn't
say that, but that's what is meant. It might be sex discrimination,
but it's disruptive to the school.''
   Martinez, a member of the baseball team and captain of the
soccer team, said he feels ``more comfortable in shorts than in
jeans. I never wear long pants unless I have to.''
   ``The kids in California are allowed to wear shorts to school,''
he said. ``I guess they're a bunch of illiterate dropouts because
of it.''
   The School Board has scheduled a public hearing next week to
consider changes to the student dress policy.
</TEXT>
