<FIRST>r a PM-BullTrial     04-22 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bull Trial,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Win, But Not Much Money, In Bull Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DODGEVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two farmers who claimed a neighbor's
wandering bulls impregnated 32 of their heifers won a lawsuit, but
got far less money than they sought to pay for abortions on the
cows that were too young to have babies.
   An Iowa County Circuit Court jury awarded damages of $640 to
Mike and Paul Mieden on Thursday. The men had sued for $54,000.
   The $640, according to a veterinarian's testimony, would have
covered the cost to administer abortion shots to the animals. The
shots would have had no prolonged health effects.
   The trial pitting the Miedens against their neighbor, Lloyd
Vivian, began Monday.
   The Miedens claimed that in late June and early July 1986, two
of Vivian's bulls jumped a fence and bred with 32 of the 86 heifers
that were in an adjacent pasture.
   The Miedens claimed that the heifers were too young to be bred,
and that they lost milk production because of the early pregnancies.
   Vivian did not deny that his bulls were in the pasture with the
heifers, but took the position that the Miedens could have done
something to prevent damage to the heifers. He offered to have the
heifers' pregnancies checked and to pay to have the pregnancies
aborted.
   Paul Mieden said four of the heifers were aborted by a
veterinarian, four aborted on their own and calves delivered by the
other 24 heifers died. Two heifers died while giving birth, he
said, and others suffered damaged reproductive tracts because they
were too young to deliver.
</TEXT>
