<FIRST>r a PM-LottoFever     04-22 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lotto Fever,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania's Super 7 Jackpot Guaranteed to Hit A Record $70 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA C. HUSLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of tickets have already been
bought for the chance to win the Pennsylvania lottery's jackpot of
$70 million, which is sure to grow, but lottery officials are
urging people not to splurge on tickets.
   The Super 7 jackpot, guaranteed to reach the $70 million mark by
Wednesday's drawing, would break North American records, lottery
spokeswoman Terry Murphy said Friday.
   Ticket sales for the Super 7 game have been booming, she said.
Players bought nearly 7 million tickets Thursday and Friday.
   Lottery officials will continue to update the jackpot's value as
sales continue, Ms. Murphy said.
   Despite the temptation to buy as many tickets as possible to
increase chances of winning, to do so would be futile, Ms. Murphy
said.
   ``The odds of winning the jackpot are one in 9.6 million for
each ticket you buy,'' she said. ``There's no way you could cover
it all.''
   Players should only use extra money to buy tickets, not money
they need to cover bills, food, clothing or other essentials, she
said.
   ``We are after players' discretionary dollars, the same money
they would spend buying a magazine or a candy bar,'' she said.
   If one person gets a ticket with seven of the 11 winning
numbers, he or she would receive $2.69 million a year for 26 years.
   The Super 7 jackpot is guaranteed to reach $70 million because
no one has bought a winning ticket for the past six weeks. That
would surpass any of the lottery jackpots ever offered in the
United States, Canada and Mexico, Ms. Murphy said.
   Prior to the Super 7 jackpot, the largest U.S. lottery winnings
were $69.9 million in Illinois, split by four ticket holders on
April 15.
   Before the $70 million prize, Pennsylvania's largest jackpot was
$46 million in the Super 7 game, which was won by a Hollidaysburg
couple on Oct. 14, 1987.
</TEXT>
