<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Disarmament     04-22 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Disarmament,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Conference Ends With Denouncement Of Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KYOTO, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Nations conference on disarmament
that ended today gave unanimous backing to a global ban on chemical
weapons, officials said.
   ``There has been a proliferation of chemical weapons and we have
to be careful,'' said Yasushi Akashi, undersecretary-general for
disarmament affairs at the U.N. ``We may not be able to close
Pandora's box.''
   Akashi and others at the four-day conference noted that 20 to 30
countries now possess chemical arms, some of which were used most
recently in the Iran-Iraq conflict that left more than 1 million
people dead.
   There was universal agreement among the 100 arms control experts
that a complete ban on chemical weapons should be negotiated at the
U.N.'s permanent Conference on Disarmament in Geneva.
   Experts from the United States, the Soviet Union and 28 other
nations gathered in Kyoto for the conference, which was held in the
only country to be the victim of nuclear attacks. In August, 1945,
the United States dropped atom bombs on the western cities of
Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
   At the meeting, experts and officials clashed over the need for
a comprehensive nuclear test ban, and on the policy of nuclear
deterrence.
   Seismologists from around the world agreed that modern
technology can produce highly accurate methods of detecting
underground nuclear explosions, but said they needed political
support and funds to build a global network of seismological
monitoring stations.
   The United States, Britian and France advocated the policy of
possessing nuclear arms to deter others from using them, while
others noted their threatening and dangerous aspects.
   On Friday, U.S. Ambassador Maynard W. Glitman told the assembly
that despite unilateral reductions in Soviet troops and
conventional arms to be carried out by next year, the United States
would continue to stockpile nuclear arms to maintain global
security.
   Glitman told reporters today that the next goal of the United
States in arms controls negotiations is the reduction of Soviet
conventional forces in Europe.
   ``To achieve an equal number for the United States and the
Soviet Union (in Europe) will enable us to look to future nuclear
reductions there,'' said Glitman, the chief U.S. negotiator for the
1987 INF (intermediate-range nuclear missiles) treaty.
</TEXT>
