<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 0545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill     04-22 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Congressman Wants `Spill Czar,' Fishermen Unhappy With Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen said they would push for a
``spill czar'' to take charge of any future oil disasters, but the
cleanup of the Exxon Valdez spill remained fractious with fishermen
demanding a bigger role.
   Forty-eight skimmers were gathering 100,000 gallons to 150,000
gallons of oil a day, the Coast Guard estimated. But officials said
Friday there were widespread delays in unloading the oil onto
barges, which Exxon spokesman Henry Beathard blamed on the crude's
thick taffy-like consistency.
   The giant Soviet oil skimmer Vaidogubsky, which spent two days
getting ready and testing its booms, was poised at Gore Point on
the Kenai Peninsula, where large pools of oil washing westward have
been stopped by a spectacular outcropping of rocks jutting into the
Gulf of Alaska. It was to begin collecting oil today.
   Heavy concentrations of oil also remained in Prince William
Sound and were on the west side of Kodiak Island, more than 300
miles to the southwest.
   More than 300 miles of shoreline have been affected since the
tanker ran aground in the sound last month and spilled 10.1 million
gallons of crude.
   Delays in responding to the spill have contributed to its
spread. Many fishermen frustrated at the lack of progress have
taken to the sea themselves, using scoops and buckets to pick up
oil contained with homemade booms.
   Kelly Duncan, 29, said he sucked 7,500 gallons of oil and
seawater into the hull of his boat. He said he fears his fishing
boat may be permanently contaminated.
   At Homer on the Kenai Peninsula, angry fishermen demanded one of
their own be given equal decision-making power with Exxon and the
Coast Guard in the cleanup.
   Reps. Don Young, R-Alaska, and Curt Weldon, R-Pa., met Friday
night with fishermen and representatives of the Coast Guard and
Exxon. ``We came out with a very positive outlook,'' Young said
without elaborating.
   The two congressmen toured oil-spotted beaches on the Kenai
Peninsula earlier in the day with Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan
Jr.
   At a news conference, the two men said they would push for
legislation to put one person _ most likely the commandant of the
Coast Guard _ in charge of cleaning up future spills.
   Commandant Paul Yost on Wednesday ended a weeklong stay in
Alaska during which he rearranged the cleanup strategy, approved an
Exxon plan for the work and set a timetable for completion. The
entire job is to be finished by mid-September.
   Young said the legislation he plans to introduce might include
funding for one oil-skimming ship to be stationed in Alaska.
   Weldon said it would be ideal to have skimmers in place on both
coasts. He was a fire chief in the Pennsylvania port town of Marcus
Hook when two foreign tankers collided there in 1975, burning and
spilling 300,000 gallons.
   Young also vowed to spend money on research and push for the use
of oil-dispersing chemicals, regardless of toxicity, in dealing
with future spills.
   Lujan didn't attend the news conference. He left the congressmen
to go to Kodiak Island, home of the nation's No. 1 fishing port and
the world's largest concentration of brown bears.
   Meanwhile, environmentalists attacked Exxon over the company's
reluctance to open a sea otter treatment center at Seward.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said Friday it had written
Exxon strongly re-emphasizing the need for a second treatment
center in addition to one at Valdez.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service has counted 3,406 dead shore
birds, 409 dead sea otters and four dead bald eagles.
</TEXT>
