<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern-Cabbies     04-22 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Cabbies,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Scraps Shuttle Marketing Effort With Cabbies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-bound Eastern Airlines says it has
stopped a program that rewarded New York cab drivers for steering
passengers toward its gates at LaGuardia Airport with $25 gift
certificates and weekly prize drawings.
   Eastern dropped the 2-week-old campaign on Friday after New
York's Taxi and Limousine Commission told the airline it was
illegal.
   ``Once it was brought to our attention, it was discontinued,''
said Jim Ashlock, an Eastern spokesman in Miami.
   Ellen Weiman, a spokeswoman for the commission, said the shuttle
incentive program for cabbies was ``against all rules,'' since taxi
drivers shouldn't be induced to take riders where they don't want
to go.
   Eastern was giving cabbies a $25 American Express certificate
for every five loads of passengers they dropped off at Eastern's
shuttle terminal at LaGuardia.
   There also was a weekly drawing for participating taxi drivers
for a color television set, videocassette recorder or radio.
   ``We'd like to think that maybe the cabbies are doing some
selling for us,'' Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said earlier
Friday. He noted that around half the passengers coming to
LaGuardia arrive by taxi.
   Eastern's hourly among New York, Boston and Washington has been
running a normal schedule, compared with only 10 percent of
pre-strike flights for the airline as a whole. Passenger loads have
been decimated, however, as the rival shuttle operated by Pan Am
Corp. has eaten into Eastern's traffic.
   Pan Am once used an incentive plan to encourage cabbies to pick
arriving passengers up at its New York terminal when the airline
started its shuttle service in late 1986, spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon
said, but the program wasn't illegal.
   She said Pan Am has captured around 80 percent of the Northeast
shuttle market, and Eastern's taxi program appears to have had no
impact.
   In another development, a Washington property developer
confirmed through an associate Friday that he is interested in
buying Eastern.
   ``We've expressed our interest; it's sincere and we're pursuing
it,'' said John Sarpa, senior vice president of Hadid Development
Co. in Roslyn, Va. The company is run by Mohamed Hadid, who
recently agreed to buy the Ritz-Carlton hotels in Washington and
New York.
   Attorneys for Eastern and its striking unions recently said
there are four serious offers for the airline, which has been
grounded by a walkout since March 4. It filed for bankruptcy
protection five days later.
   They said the bidders are ex-baseball commissioner Peter V.
Ueberroth, whose $464 million deal to buy Eastern collapsed last
week; takeover strategist Carl Icahn; billionaire hotel executive
Jay Pritzker; and an unnamed suitor.
   But Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent's Texas Air Corp.,
insisted earlier this week that Eastern isn't for sale and that
there is no serious fourth bidder.
</TEXT>
