<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Slaying     04-22 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Slaying,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Rebels Claim They Killed U.S. Colonel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels today claimed
responsibility for the ambush-slaying of a U.S. Army officer, and
said it was in retaliation for the United States' ``arrogant
trampling'' of Philippine independence.
   Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe, a former Vietnam prisoner of war, was
killed Friday by a shot to the head when gunmen in a stolen car
sprayed his vehicle with bullets while he was on his way to work in
suburban Quezon.
   The communist New People's Army General Command claimed
responsibility in a statement delivered to news agencies. The
letter bore the logo of the rebel army and was released on behalf
of its chief, Romulo Kintanar.
   The statement threatened further attacks if the United States
continues support of President Corazon Aquino's fight against the
20-year Communist insurgency.
   ``The death of Col. Rowe signifies the firm commitment of the
revolutionary forces to continue military actions against U.S.
personnel and installations as these are manifestations of the
arrogant trampling of U.S. imperialists on the Filipino people's
independence and sovereignty,'' the statement said.
   Rowe, 51, was chief of the ground forces division of the Joint
U.S.-Military Advisory Group, which provides training and
logistical support to the Philippine military.
   Rowe, a native of McAllen, Texas, was a decorated Vietnam War
hero who was held in a cage for five years by the Viet Cong as a
prisoner of war until he escaped in 1968.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt called the killing a ``cowardly''
act.
   Marlin Fitzwater, President Bush's press secretary, said the
U.S. government will work with the Philippine government ``to track
down and bring to justice those responsible for this
assassination.''
   Police said they recovered the assailants' car and traced it to
a Filipino civilian who said it was stolen on April 7. Cartridges
from bullets used in the killing littered the vehicle, police said.
   Police said up to three cars may have been used in the ambush,
but witnesses said they saw only one carrying at least three men, a
driver and two gunmen. One gunman had an M-16 rifle and the other a
.45-caliber pistol, police said.
   Rowe's Filipino driver was wounded in the attack.
   It came five days after the communist National Democratic Front
said the rebels were ``determined to make U.S. imperialism pay
dearly for the continuing stay of its bases and its escalating
intervention in our people's affairs.''
   The statement was issued to claim reponsibility for the bombing
of a U.S. communications station in the northern province of
Benguet on April 9. No one was hurt.
   In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino
outside Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of Manila. Authorities then
increased security at six U.S. military installations and civilian
offices in the Philippines.
   The U.S. Navy today ordered additional security for the 1,000
sailors on the flagship USS Blue Ridge of the 7th Fleet. The ship
arrived Friday for a four-day port call.
   Lt. Mike Andrews, the fleet's spokesman, said the sailors were
told, among other things, to travel in groups and stay away from
dark alleys.
   In Washington, State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher
said Friday that a U.S. travel advisory issued March 15 ``indicates
areas of the country where, because of criminal activity or
terrorist activity, people should try to avoid.''
   The advisory says most urban areas in the Philippines including
Manila are safe for travelers.
   Boucher indicated the advisory might be revised. ``I'm sure that
will be looked at,'' he said. ``I would note that the threats that
I have heard about were against official Americans, and weren't
general threats to travelers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
