<DOCNO> AP890422-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 0609EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Mecham     04-22 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mecham,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General: Mecham Can Run Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham can run for public office
again despite the impeachment and conviction that ousted him a year
ago, the attorney general said.
   ``Naturally `I'm happy about it,'' said Mecham, who has already
announced a 1990 gubernatorial bid.
   ``It's what we thought it should be,'' he told television
station KPNX from Omaha, Neb.
   The opinion issued Friday by Attorney General Bob Corbin is
nonbinding and could be challenged in court, but political leaders
from both parties said they wouldn't challenge it.
   ``I think this issue should be settled by the voters of
Arizona,'' said Phoenix developer J. Fife Symington III, who has
announced he will run against Mecham in next year's GOP primary.
   Corbin said Mecham was free to run becafice in the future. The
impeachment and conviction did not disqualify Mecham automatically,
he said.
   His attorney, Donald MacPherson, said that Mecham originally had
intended to ``take this question of the `Dracula clause' to the
Supreme Court regardless of Bob Corbin's opinion.''
   The Republican-controlled Senate ousted Mecham on April 4, 1988,
by more than the required two-thirds vote. But by a vote of 17-13 _
three short of a two-thirds majority _ the Senate failed to invoke
the so-called ``Dracula clause'' that would have driven a political
stake through Mecham's heart and barred him from holding office
again.
   Some legal scholars have said the Senate might not have needed
to vote on the clause because the state's constitution speaks of
ouster and disqualification in the same sentence. And even if a
separate vote was required, they said, a simple majority such as
17-13 might be enough.
   But in his 11-page opinion, Corbin said those who wrote the
state's Constitution expected that there would be separate votes on
ouster and disqualification.
   Political leaders from both parties welcomed the opinion and
said it would be better to let Mecham go ahead with his campaign
for 1990.
   ``I think he ought to be able to run,'' said Senate President
Robert Usdane, a Republican who voted to oust Mecham but also voted
against the ``Dracula clause.''
   ``I think it'd be better that he not be martyred,'' Usdane added.
   Senate Minority Leader Alan Stephens, a Democrat who also voted
for impeachment and against the ``Dracula clause,'' said Corbin's
ruling ``is the right decision.''
   Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford, who succeeded Mecham following his
ouster, said the attorney general's opinion would not change her
plans to run for governor in 1990.
   Mecham was elected on his fifth try for governor in 1986 and was
impeached by the House after barely a year in office.
   The articles of impeachment charged Mecham with concealing a
developer's campaign loan, misusing state money and obstructing
justice.
   The Senate convicted Mecham on the misuse of funds and
obstruction charges but deferred the obstruction charge to Superior
Court, where he was acquitted.
   MacPherson said Mecham still plans to ask the state Supreme
Court next month to set aside the impeachment.
   ``We still have high hopes of either having the articles of
impeachment dismissed, which would put Gov. Mecham immediately back
in office, or having a new trial declared,'' MacPherson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
