<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 0632EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LouisianaSpill     04-22 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Spill,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spill Downgraded; Employee Not Certfied, Says Coast Guard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAYOU SORREL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears for a fragile bayou environment
were receding after officials downgraded the estimated size of a
spill of oil-tainted water to no more than 10,000 gallons.
   Meanwhile, the Coast Guard said an employee who was transferring
the waste water from a barge when the spill occurred lacked proper
certification.
   The spill of so-called ``slop water'' occurred early Friday on a
loading dock on Grand River, about 35 miles southwest of Baton
Rouge, said Bobby Mayweather of GSX Land Treatment in nearby White
Castle.
   The barge was carrying 900,000 gallons of waste water from an
Exxon plant in Houston. It buckled in the middle while the waste
was being unloaded into tanker trucks, Mayweather said.
   Authorities said the spill was quickly contained and that a
cleanup would continue today.
   Exxon had paid GSX to treat and dispose of the waste at White
Castle, Mayweather said.
   Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Dean Kutz said one of the companies or an
individual could be assessed civil penalties for conducting the
transfer without proper documentation.
   Coast Guard Chief Warrant Officer Larry Doss said GSX employee
Gordon Vice didn't have the required Merchant Marine certification
for the job.
   Rick Davenport, facility manager for the GSX recovery unit in
Crowley, confirmed that Vice was manning the operation when the
spill occurred, but he declined to comment further. GSX is assuming
responsibility for the cleanup, Davenport said.
   The barge was leased by GSX and Exxon had no responsibility for
the shipment after it left the Texas site, said Iberville Parish
Sheriff Freddie Pitre.
   Paul Dubois, a spokesman for the Palmer Co., owner of the barge,
said waste water is used to wash out tanks and ships.
   Louisiana State Police Lt. Ronnie Jones said that according to
Exxon, the waste was about 90 percent water, 7 percent alcohol and
3 percent light oil.
   State Police initially estimated the spill at up to 400,000
gallons, while GSX estimated it at 180,000 gallons. Exxon Chemical
spokeswoman Jill Johnson in Dallas downgraded the estimate late
Friday to about 10,000 gallons.
   No one was injured in the accident, but Johnson said a small
number of fish were killed at the outset.
   ``It looked like a giant had stepped on the barge smack in the
middle,'' said Jones. ``Oil-absorbing booms were in place shortly
after the spill and we believe most of the waste was confined to
the immediate area of Grand River.
   ``Things could have been an awful lot worse but because of the
waste involved and the quick response by Iberville Parish
officials, we've got a good handle on the situation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
