<FIRST>r a PM-SonoraSlayings     04-22 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sonora Slayings,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sonoran Murders Suspect, Being Held Without Bond, Denies Complicity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man identified as the principal suspect
in a dozen drug-related torture slayings in Mexico near the U.S.
border denied he was the killer but said he may have information on
the deaths, officials said.
   Hector Fragoso Burgueno, 45, was held without bond Friday at the
Federal Correctional Center after his arrest late Thursday at a
mobile home in an isolated area about 30 miles west of Tucson.
   ``He's the principal one, according to the witnesses,'' said
Enrique Cecena, zone commander with the Judicial Police of the
Mexican state of Sonora.
   Mexican federal and state authorities will file formal requests
for Fragoso's return to Mexico, officials said.
   Gerard Murphy, a Drug Enforcement Administration special agent,
said Fragoso ``has made statements extricating himself from any
culpability in the murders in Agua Prieta. However, he has said
that he may be able to provide information that authorities are not
aware of.''
   Fragoso was found with a woman identified as his wife, Anna
Marie Fragoso. Scott Coffin, deputy chief agent for the U.S. Border
Patrol in Tucson, said Fragoso was being held as an illegal alien
under a federal immigration arrest warrant. His wife could be
voluntarily deported to Mexico, officials said.
   Fragoso owned the ranch near the Mexican border town of Agua
Prieta where the bodies were found on March 29 and April 1. He had
shaved his moustache, changed his hair style and altered his
eyebrows, but ``it didn't help him. We recognized him right away,''
said Pima County Sheriff's Maj. Dennis Douglas.
   Douglas said investigators found Fragoso after getting various
tips, including some from a local crime hotline and from the TV
show ``America's Most Wanted,'' which had a segment Sunday on
Fragoso.
   Authorities were investigating whether the Agua Prieta killings
were linked to the slayings of five people whose bodies were found
in a Tucson shed shortly before the Agua Prieta bodies were
discovered.
   Cecena said 11 of the Agua Prieta victims apparently were killed
after they witnessed the murder of one person.
   The Border Patrol said Fragoso has an extensive arrest history,
ranging from drug and weapons violations to assault, sexual assault
and robbery.
   Like the unrelated ritual slayings of 15 people in Matamoros
discovered last week, authorities consider the Agua Prieta killings
to be drug-related.
</TEXT>
