<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     04-22 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Fire Rockets At Christian Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian forces today fired rockets into
the port of Jounieh, the only escape route for Lebanon's
beleaguered Christians.
   No casualties were reported as sporadic 122mm Soviet-designed
Grad rockets exploded around Jounieh, 10 miles north of Beirut, and
the coastal highway running north to the ancient port of Byblos.
   The attack came during a three-day lull in the battle between
the Syrians and allied Moslem Druse militia and the mainly
Christian units of Lebanon's fractured armed forces under army
commander Gen. Michel Aoun.
   By police count, at least 270 people have been killed and nearly
1,000 wounded in ferocious artillery, rocket and tank exchanges
that began March 8 in the divided capital.
   Police, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported that an
estimated 4,000 Christians were gathered at Jounieh to await
ferries from Cyprus, 130 miles to the northeast, to take them to
safety.
   The 4,000-ton Baroness M, one of two ferries that have carried
12,000 Christians to Cyprus in the last six weeks, was anchored off
Jounieh on Friday night. It took 1,200 people from Jounieh in small
boats.
   The other ferry, the Larnaca Rose, suspended its Jounieh run
three days ago after it came under Syrian shelling near the
lebanese port.
   Cypriot shipping officials said it was not known when the next
ferry will sail for Jounieh.
   Beirut's Moslem-controlled Voice of the Nation today termed the
Syrian rocketing a warning to ships to stay away from the besieged
enclave. ``It will persist as long as the blockade imposed by Aoun
perists,'' it said.
   The latest fighting broke out two days after Aoun, seeking to
restore state authority, blockaded illegal ports south of Beirut
run by Moslem militias.
   Aoun's troops in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, which is
ringed on the three landward sides by hostile forces, have not
returned the Syrian fire since most fighting died down late
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
