<FIRST>u a PM-WinerySlayings 1stLd-Writethru a0450 04-22 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0450,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Charged With Seven Murders; Will Return For Plea</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to raise reference to automatic teller machines
and tighten; PICKS UP 18th graf pvs, `After his ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automatic teller machines helped
police track down a winery worker accused of murdering seven
people, including his wife and two daughters.
   The Sonoma County sheriff's office persuaded Wells Fargo Bank to
extend unlimited credit to Ramon Salcido and arranged to track him
through any transactions made with his automatic teller card, said
Sheriff Dick Michaelsen.
   A tip from Salcido's sister and brother-in-law in Mexico also
helped authorities find him, the San Francisco Chronicle reported
today, citing unidentified U.S. diplomatic and law enforcement
sources.
   Salcido, 28, who also is accused of killing his mother-in-law
and her two daughters and a co-worker at the winery where he was a
forklift operator, was arraigned on murder charges Friday after
being captured in Mexico.
   Salcido was reported to have run out of bank funds last week
while on a cocaine-and-alcohol binge that friends said preceded the
April 14 slaughter.
   He tried to use a bank card at least once at a Wells Fargo
branch that morning in San Rafael, 30 miles south, and possibly
again later in San Francisco while heading for Mexico, authorities
said.
   The manhunt ended Wednesday when Salcido was arrested in western
Mexico near his hometown of Los Mochis.
   A spokesman for the sheriff's department, citing a gag order
imposed by a judge on Friday, would not comment on the report about
family members tipping off police.
   Salcido, who also is charged with three counts of attempted
murder, appeared in court Friday in handcuffs and a bulletproof
vest. He did not enter a plea but will return to court May 5. He
could get the death penalty if convicted.
   Salcido's attorney, Chief Public Defender Marteen Miller said he
expected Salcido would enter a plea of innocent by reason of
insanity. He added that he would have his client undergo
psychiatric and neurological tests.
   ``I expect to find some brain lesion or tumor,'' said Miller,
who called the crimes, ``so bizarre, so incomprehensible.''
   ``God, I hope I find something,'' said Miller, who also planned
to ask that the trial be moved because of all the publicity the
case has received.
   The prosecutor, however, discounted speculation that the rampage
was fueled in part by alcohol and cocaine us and said he believed
Salcido is legally sane.
   ``The final decision about his state of mind will be made in
court,'' said District Attorney Gene Tunney. ``Those were not the
acts of an irrational berserker.''
   After his arrest, Salcido told Mexican television reporters and
law enforcement agents he killed his American-born wife, Angela,
24, and a winery co-worker, Tracy Toovey, in a jealous rage,
believing Toovey and his wife were romantically involved, according
to federal officials.
   Also killed in the series of attacks across the Sonoma Valley 40
miles north of San Francisco were Salcido's mother-in-law and his
two sisters-in-law, 8 and 12.
   Salcido also is accused of killing two daughters, 1 and 4, who
were found dead at a dump April 15. Their throats had been slashed.
   Another daughter, Carmina, who turns 3 on Monday, also was found
at the dump with a slashed throat but is recovering and has
identified her father as her attacker, police said.
</TEXT>
