<SECOND>PM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Rebels Kill Seven In Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to CORRECT spelling of Sindangan in 3rd graf
and fix typo in 4th graf. Pickup 5th pvs, ``In nearby...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAGADIAN, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected communist guerrillas
attacked the homes of two government militiamen in the southern
Philippines today. Seven people, including three children and one
militiaman, were killed, police said.
   A police report said the attack, with automatic rifles and
grenade launchers, occurred in the remote town of Sindangan in
Zamboanga del Norte province, 40 miles northwest of Pagadian and
460 miles southeast of Manila.
   Sgt. Gideon Rodrigo, the Sindangan police station commander,
said about 30 members of the communist New People's Army fired
simultaneously on the two houses with M-16 rifles and M-203 grenade
launchers. Seven occupants were killed and five were wounded,
including the militiaman who survived, he said.
   Rodrigo said government militiamen owned the homes and that the
attack was in retaliation for their participation in the
government's campaign against the rebels. The insurgents took away
the militiamen's farm animals, he said.
   In nearby Zamboanga del Sur province, two militiamen were killed
Friday when about 200 rebels attacked the town of Mahayag and held
residents for nearly one hour before escaping, a military report
said. It said the rebels issued a challenge to soldiers in the area
and fought with them for 30 minutes.
   In another attack Friday, rebels killed two militiamen in the
town of Molave in adjoining Misamis Oriental province, the military
said.
</TEXT>
