<FIRST>r i PM-Walesa     04-22 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Says Solidarity Destined to Shrink</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said today that the
East bloc's first independent trade union probably will get smaller
as other independent groups form in Poland.
   ``From Solidarity, other economic and political organizations
will be born,'' Walesa said at a news conference ending his
three-day visit to Italy.
   ``Solidarity for the moment is huge but it will become smaller
with the growth of other organizations. This is the logical course
of events.''
   The Polish independent trade union was crushed by security
forces in 1981 and outlawed in 1982. Poland's communist government
restored the legality of Solidarity on Monday after reaching
agreement with the Solidarity-led opposition on political and
social reforms.
   The government is seeking support from Solidarity and aid from
the West to restore its shattered economy.
   Coinciding with the official recognition of Solidarity,
President Bush announced a $1 billion economic aid program for
Poland. Walesa said the program was ``a great step forward taken by
Mr. Bush.''
   Walesa, winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, indicated he
planned to visit other countries as an ``ambassador of Solidarity''
but did not say which ones.
   Walesa came to Italy seeking economic investment in Poland and
the blessing of fellow Pole Pope John Paul II for the country's new
political course.
   The Solidarity leader said he would like to see the pope make
another trip to Poland but that John Paul had many obligations.
   ``And because we love him, we will spare him,'' Walesa said.
   ``For this reason, we told him not to worry so much about Poland
_ we have reached these accords, worry yourself less. It's clear,
though, that he won't listen to us and will continue to be
concerned.''
</TEXT>
