<FIRST>r a PM-PentagonFraud     04-22 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon Fraud,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Given Prison Terms In Probe Of Procurement Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Pentagon employee and a
dismissed executive of Hazeltine Corp., a defense contractor, have
been given prison terms stemming from the ``Ill Wind''
investigation of military procurement corruption.
   U.S. District Court Judge Claude M. Hilton on Friday sentenced
Jack A. Sherman, 52, a one-time civilian Marine Corps contracting
supervisor, to 18 months in prison for taking $43,500 in bribes
from an unidentified defense consultant in exchange for inside
information on military contracts.
   Hilton also sentenced former Hazeltine vice president Joseph R.
Colarusso, 58, to 10 months in prison and fined him $30,000 for
improperly obtaining inside information about a $150 million Navy
electronics contract sought by Hazeltine last year.
   Colarusso pleaded guilty in January to conspiracy to defraud the
federal government and to commit wire fraud in connection with his
hiring of a defense consultant who obtained the inside data by
bribing a Navy engineer.
   Also in January, Sherman pleaded guilty to bribery and
conspiracy and agreed to pay federal taxes on his unreported bribe
income. He will also pay back the $43,500, which was supplied by
the FBI. The consultant who passed the money to Sherman was working
as an FBI informant.
</TEXT>
