<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Abortion Bjt   04-22 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Abortion, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Considers Limiting Women's Right to Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court hears arguments this week on
limiting _ or even ending _ women's abortion rights, but the battle
is sure to continue no matter what is decided in the Missouri case
before the justices.
   The dispute over the Missouri abortion-regulation law, for which
arguments will be conducted Wednesday, has become one of history's
most closely watched high court cases.
   There are two reasons:
   _Missouri officials and the Bush administration are urging the
court to use the case to overturn or substantially limit the
landmark 1973 decision legalizing abortion.
   _Even if the court does not accept that invitation and decides
the Missouri case narrowly, the decision _ expected in July _ will
be viewed as a barometer of the current court's commitment to the
16-year-old ruling in Roe vs. Wade.
   ``If Roe is reversed, the nation's whole political landscape
could change,'' said Kate Michelman, executive director of the
National Abortion Rights Action League. ``State by state, our goal
would be obtaining a legislative right to abortion, making the lack
of any constitutional right irrelevant.''
   She added: ``It no longer would be acceptable for any politician
to be anti-choice.''
   Reversal of the 1973 ruling would allow states to more
stringently restrict access to abortions, or even ban virtually all
abortions.
   James Bopp, general counsel of the anti-abortion National Right
to Life Committee, said, ``Roe vs. Wade is doomed at some point in
the foreseeable future but the pro-choice people are laying the
legal groundwork for other attacks on restrictions, already arguing
that they amount to gender-based discrimination or involuntary
servitude.''
   And if the 1973 decision emerges unscathed by the court's
decision in the Missouri case?
   ``We (in the pro-choice movement) would still be vulnerable,''
Michelman said in a recent interview.
   Laurie Ann Ramsey, director of education for Americans United
for Life, agreed. ``Reversal by 1992 is part of our strategic plan.
If not in (the Missouri case), then in the next'' she said. ``We
want to keep as many cases in the pipeline as possible.''
   Michelman's apprehension and Ramsey's confidence stem from
changes in the high court's membership since it ruled, by a 7-2
vote, in 1973 that women have a constitutional right to abortion.
   Only three members of the original Roe vs. Wade majority remain
_ Justices Harry A. Blackmun, William J. Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall. Each has supported the 1973 decision in subsequent
rulings.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, who joined the court in 1975, is a
dependable ``pro-Roe'' ally.
   The two 1973 dissenters, now-Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justice Byron R. White, still oppose the ruling.
   Any significant retreat from Roe vs. Wade will have to attract
the court's three most junior justices _ Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   All are appointees of former president Ronald Reagan, an
outspoken critic of the high court's abortion rulings.
   O'Connor criticized the rationale of Roe vs. Wade while
dissenting from a 1986 decision striking down certain abortion
regulations in Pennsylvania. But it is unknown whether she
disagrees with the core holding of the 1973 decision _ that women
have a fundamental right to abortion.
   Scalia and Kennedy have not yet ruled in any abortion case, but
many believe both favor cutting back abortion rights.
   ``Justice O'Connor is the key,'' NARAL's Michelman said. ``We
wrote our (friend-of-the-court) brief to speak to Sandra Day
O'Connor.''
   Dawn Johnsen, the NARAL legal director who wrote the brief,
said, ``If we are going to win it's likely to be by one vote.
That's not the kind of victory with which one can be comfortable.''
   In all, the justices received a record 78 friend-of-the-court
briefs _ the judicial branch's equivalent of lobbying _ from
interested individuals and organizations not actually involved of
the Missouri dispute.
   The justices often give such unsolicited advice close attention.
   The same cannot be said, however, for the tens of thousands of
letters and hundreds of telephone calls the court is receiving
daily from Americans expressing their views on abortion.
   ``This is not a popularity contest,'' court spokeswoman Toni
House said. ``This is a war of ideas, not numbers.''
   If a war, it is one with no end in sight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890422-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Abortion-Justices     04-22 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Justices,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thumbnail Views of Nine Justices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the views of each
Supreme Court member on the court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision,
reached by a 7-2 vote, that women have a constitutional right to
abortion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SUPPORTERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Justice Harry A. Blackmun, 80. He authored the landmark Roe vs.
Wade opinion and is its most impassioned champion on the court. He
told a law school audience last fall the court might reverse the
1973 ruling this term. ``You can count the votes,'' he said.
   _Justice William J. Brennan, 82. A Roman Catholic, he reportedly
steered the court's closed-door deliberations that led to the 1973
ruling and joined in Blackmun's majority opinion.
   _Justice Thurgood Marshall, 80. He is the third remaining member
of the Roe vs. Wade majority.
   _Justice John Paul Stevens, 68. Since joining the court in 1975,
he consistently has voted to uphold the abortion right.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OPPONENTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, 64. He was a dissenter in
1973 and, in subsequent abortion rulings, has voted to give states
far greater authority to regulate abortions.
   _Justice Byron R. White, 71. The second dissenter from Roe vs.
Wade, he said in a subsequent abortion opinion that the 1973
decision ``essentially created something out of nothing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SWING VOTES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, 58. In a dissenting vote in 1986,
she favored giving states more authority in regulating abortions
and criticized the legal approach taken by Blackmun in 1973. But
she has never said that women do not have a constitutional right to
abortion.
   _Justice Antonin Scalia, 52. He never participated in an
abortion case as a federal appeals court judge, and since joining
the high court in 1986 has taken no public stand on abortion.
   _Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, 52. Although a federal appeals
court judge for 12 years before joining the court last year, he
never has ruled in an abortion case nor has he stated his views
publicly on the issue.
</TEXT>
