<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral     04-22 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Voters Wonder How Long They'll Remain on the Sidelines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley's march to City Hall by
defeating two blacks has left the black vote in disarray and has
many wondering whether Daley's inauguration Monday will be his
first and only or the first of many.
   Daley, son of the last of the big-city bosses, ended blacks'
six-year grip on the mayoralty by soundly beating acting Mayor
Eugene Sawyer in February's Democratic primary and by doing the
same to Alderman Timothy Evans six weeks later.
   Daley will complete the last two years of the second term of the
city's first black mayor, Harold Washington, who died in 1987.
   Daley's father, Richard J. Daley, won six consecutive terms.
Whether the younger Daley is in for the long term may depend less
on his own actions than on whether black voters can regroup after
splintering between Sawyer and Evans.
   ``We knew what the stakes were this time around and we let it
get away from us once. ... So I'm taking a dismal view of things
for the future,'' said Lu Palmer, an influential black radio
commentator and political activist,
   ``I don't see any possibility of winning the mayor's office back
by 1991, and let's face it, if Daley gets a foothold then,'' he
said, ``the office is probably his until the year
2000-and-something.''
   Most election post-mortems have centered on the low black
turnout that crippled both Sawyer and Evans, despite the efforts of
former Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson on behalf of
both.
   The ensuing debate among blacks has centered on whether they
should spend their time on the sidelines developing a black
independent party, as Palmer suggests, or try to rebuild the
multiracial coalition that lifted Washington to power in 1983 and
made him the first mayor since the elder Daley to be re-elected.
   ``The reason Harold won _ and make no mistake about it _ is
because he was able to graft liberal whites and Hispanics onto that
huge bloc,'' said Clarence Page, a black who is a member of the
Chicago Tribune's editorial board.
   ``It doesn't have to be tomorrow, but blacks should begin the
process of looking for a candidate to do that. ... To suggest they
sit on the sidelines and wait until the numbers grow enough to go
it alone ... is just short-sighted.''
   The city has roughly equal numbers of blacks and whites, but
whites make up about 49 percent of the electorate, compared with
about 43 percent for blacks.
   Don Rose, a veteran political strategist who held top posts in
the Washington and Evans campaigns, said Daley won ``because a lot
of white liberals and people who joined Washington's reform
movement were willing to give him a chance and because a lot of
blacks didn't feel a sufficient amount of outrage and didn't vote.''
   ``What Daley has to do now is make good on his campaign promises
to be inclusive, racially and ethnically, in terms of appointments
and contracts and promote reform-minded legislation,'' Rose said.
``If he doesn't, the movement had better be ready.''
</TEXT>
