<FIRST>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0434 04-22 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0434,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>August Space Shuttle Flight Delayed At Least Three Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, `Then will ...' to CORRECT from Atlantis
to Discovery.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two military space shuttle flights
planned next summer will be delayed, one for at least three months,
because work on the shuttle Columbia is taking longer than expected.
   NASA said Friday the schedule had become too tight to support
both missions and still preserve an October launch for the
high-priority Galileo flight to Jupiter.
   A Discovery launch that had been scheduled for Aug. 10 will be
delayed until at least November. Columbia, which had a July 1
launch target, will be launched in early August, the space agency
said.
   Both missions are to deploy classified Defense Department
payloads.
   Unaffected will be Friday's planned liftoff of Atlantis with the
Magellan-Venus spacecraft on board, the first planet-bound payload
scheduled for release from a space shuttle.
   The schedule changes will have a ripple effect on launch dates
later in the year, leaving NASA with six instead of its goal of
seven shuttle launches this year.
   Officials have said the planned Oct. 12 liftoff of Atlantis with
the Jupiter-orbiting Galileo spacecraft is a high-priority flight
because there is only a 40-day launch period during which Jupiter
and Earth are aligned properly. So it will be next in line after
Columbia's August mission.
   Then will come the delayed Discovery military flight, probably
in November, and a flight, probably in December, in which
Columbia's crew is to deploy a communications satellite and
retrieve a science satellite which has been orbiting since 1984.
   The mission of Discovery with the Hubble Space Telescope, long
awaited by astronomers, will slip from its present December launch
slot into 1990.
   NASA said dates for missions after the Galileo flight will be
determined later.
   ``NASA management has become increasingly concerned that the
work involved in preparing the orbiter Columbia for its first
flight in over three years is taking long enough that it might
endanger the option to launch Galileo at the opening of the launch
window,'' said shuttle chief Richard H. Truly. ``Our overriding
objectives in this situation are to protect the Galileo window and
to fly Columbia as early as we can.''
   Following the Challenger explosion in January 1986, the shuttle
fleet was grounded for 32 months while the three remaining orbiters
underwent major modifications to improve safety and performance.
   The modified Discovery has made two flights since the accident
and Atlantis is about to make its second.
   Besides the Challenger-dictated changes, Columbia, the first
shuttle and a veteran of seven space trips, also had to undergo
extensive alterations to its thermal protection tile system and is
the last one to be returned to flight status.
   The Columbia work is taking longer than planned because of a
shortage of skilled engineers and technicians to process three
shuttles simultaneously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890422-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Life Bjt   04-22 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Life, Bjt,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Life In Lebanon: `Shaft' and Bomb Shelters</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The day Lebanon's civil war began its
15th year, 69 people were killed or wounded. Most were civilians.
   The casualties were caused by an estimated 25,000 shells and
rockets fired by Christian and Moslem forces that day, April 13.
The figures indicate it took 362 shells and rockets to inflict one
casualty.
   That's about average in the daily battles between mainly
Christian units of Lebanon's army, long fractured along sectarian
lines, and an alliance of Syrian forces and Moslem Druse militiamen.
   It costs the Syrian Army about $120,000 every time it fires a
broadside from one of its 40-barrel 240mm rocket launchers into
Christian east Beirut.
   It costs Gen. Michael Aoun's Christian army units about the same
to lob a similar number of 155mm howitzer shells into Moslem zones.
   But there is no shortage of guns or ammunition among Lebanon's
warring factions, who are well supplied by regional powers who use
Lebanon to fight their rivals by proxy.
   Leftist and Moslem militias are armed and bankrolled by Syria,
Libya and Iran. Their Christian rivals get their U.S.-made weapons
from Iraq and Israel.
   It's a strange war. There are no ground assaults. No one gains
territory or loses it. Both sides, deeply entrenched, just hammer
each other, usually with long-range weapons.
   The current round of fighting, the worst in four years, started
March 8. Since then, by police count, more than 270 people have
been killed and nearly 1,000 wounded.
   Despite the intensity of the shelling, with 50 shells and
rockets a minute falling in the worst barrages, the casualty toll
is surprisingly low.
   The reason is that after 14 years of civil war and factional
bloodletting, the Lebanese have developed a sixth sense about when
trouble is near. They know to head for underground bunkers and
basements.
   For those who haven't developed that sense, the signal to take
cover is the theme song from the movie ``Shaft'' on the radio. The
Isaac Hayes tune always precedes flashes on where shells are
falling.
   Beirutis know that when their side starts firing, a retaliatory
barrage is inevitable.
   When the big fuel depot on the Christian side was hit a few days
ago, sending up a huge fireball and destroying virtually all
Lebanon's fuel supplies, the radio advised everyone living near the
blazing facility to get away in case other fuel tanks blew.
   A distraught Christian mother of three told how she rushed out
of her apartment with her family amid the thud of exploding shells
nearby.
   It was only when she reached her brother's house in the
neighboring Hazmieh district that she realized she'd left her son
with a neighbor.
   Three hours later, the 10-year-old boy showed up. He had walked
three miles under heavy shelling without a scratch.
   ``Those were the worst hours of my life,'' said the young woman.
She did not want to be identified, ``because my husband works
abroad and I don't want him to hear about this.''
   But despite their well-honed survival instincts, people are
sometimes caught off guard.
   A young Moslem named Jamal was killed by shrapnel as he drove
his family from his home in the south Beirut district of Ouzai to
west Beirut to be with his elderly mother during a lull a few days
ago, his neighbors said.
   A 25-year-old Druse student, just back from West Germany where
he majored in computer science, was killed when he visited a
militia base manned by fighters of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's
Progressive Socialist Party.
   ``We'd asked him to teach us how to use communications
equipment,'' a fighter said. ``A shell landed close to where we
were standing and he was killed.''
   The bunkers have become second homes for many families. For many
Beirutis, life underground is austere and cramped. Power plants
have been hit or shut down because fuel has run out.
   Fires rage out of control because the water pumping system
doesn't work, because there's no power.
   Several families are often crammed into reinforced basements for
days on end, eating from stockpiles of canned food and water,
sleeping as best they can by the light of kerosene lamps or candles.
   For the well-off, bunker life can be almost comfortable.
   Fourteen Christian families living in the Adonis district of
east Beirut have constructed a luxury two-story bunker under their
apartment block.
   One of them, furniture store owner Hanna Breidi, has fitted it
with wall-to-wall carpets, 10 double beds, armchairs, refrigerators
and a small gambling salon.
   They also have two color television sets with video recorders,
and radio telephones, which operate independently of their
generator. There are video games for the children.
   The fridge is stocked with smoked salmon, hams, imported
cheeses, steaks and wine.
   The families' maids, mostly Sri Lankans and Filipinas, live on
the first floor below ground level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890422-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-JunkBondDebt     04-22 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Junk Bond Debt,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: for release at 5:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Many Companies Carry Too Much High-Risk Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress may be asked to bail out numerous
corporations that will be forced into bankruptcy in the next
recession because of excessive debt, the chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee said Saturday.
   Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said a study that shows a spectacular
increase in the amount of high-risk ``junk bond'' debt since 1980
makes him worry about the possibility of a taxpayer bailout similar
to the multibillion dollar rescue of the nation's troubled savings
and loans.
   Bentsen said the Library of Congress study ``tells us that the
amount of corporate debt is going through the roof and that the
quality of corporate debt is going through the floor.''
   In 1980, one out of 25 bonds was below investment grade; today
it is one out of five, Bentsen said. Corporate debt has tripled
since 1980.
   ``When we see another recession _ and ultimately we will _
you're going to see that recession deeper and longer because of
this great increase in debt and some of these highly leveraged
corporations,'' said Bentsen.
   ``And then you'll see so many of them going bankrupt that you'll
begin to hear cries for having the taxpayers going in and bailing
them out like we had to do on the savings and loan industry and
that gives me very deep concern,'' Bentsen said.
   The study said more than $30 billion in junk bonds was issued in
the last three years, accounting for more than 20 percent of
outstanding corporate debt.
   Bentsen said his committee would be examining a way of limiting
the attractiveness of corporate debt.
</TEXT>
