<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Cuba     04-22 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Cuba,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Receives Two Cuban Bishops; Papal Visit Envisioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II met Saturday with two
senior churchmen from Cuba, whose Communist government is
reportedly preparing to extend an official invitation for a
first-ever papal visit.
   The Vatican said the pope met for 20 minutes with Archbishop
Jaime Lucas Ortega y Alamino of Havana, president of the Cuban
bishops' conference, and Bishop Mariano Vivanco Valiente of
Matanzas.
   It was listed as a private audience, and no details were
released.
   Vatican officials said last week that an envoy of Cuban
President Fidel Castro was expected at the Vatican soon.
   The Miami Herald, citing religious sources in Cuba, reported
that Jose Felipe Carneado, director of the Cuban Communist Party's
Office of Religious Affairs, would travel to Rome with a formal
invitation for the pope to visit Cuba.
   Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, a top Vatican official who visited
Cuba in late December, reported ``inequivocal signs'' of
improvement in church-state relations there and said he discussed
the possibility of a papal visit.
   The Miami Herarld said its sources suggested the papal visit
would be scheduled sometime in 1990 or 1991.
   Cuba has been officially atheist since the Communist revolution
30 years ago, but the Holy See and the Vatican have maintained
diplomatic relations.
   Last month, the pope applauded improvements in the church's
ability to carry out its mission in Cuba but made no mention of a
possible visit.
   In January, Castro said the pope is welcome in Cuba and is
appreciated by the entire population ``as a high-profile and
influential international leader.''
