<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e AM-Opera     04-22 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Opera,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Serves Up Refreshing Elixir</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For those to whom a heavy diet of Wagner's
``Ring Cycle'' is poison, the Metropolitan Opera has an antidote
that's easy to swallow _ an ``Elixir of Love'' with superstars
Luciano Pavarotti and Kathleen Battle.
   Donizetti's comic masterpiece _ which he dashed off in an
amazing two weeks _ made its first appearance of the season Friday
night to a standing-room-only crowd.
   It will be performed four more times during the final two weeks
of the season, while most of the Met's attention is devoted to its
new staging of Wagner's four-part ``Der Ring Des Nibelungen.''
   Luckily, this fading but still charming 1960 production by
Nathaniel Merrill and Robert O'Hearn practically runs by itself,
like a windup clock. And with music so effervescent and a plot so
foolproof, the audience is guaranteed a good time, even if the
performance never quite sparkles as it should.
   Pavarotti started his career singing light tenor roles like
Nemorino, the bumbling country bumpkin who tries to win the heart
of his true love by drinking a magic potion. He's gone on to tackle
heavier parts _ and lost some of his luster in the process _ but
this role remains a favorite.
   Though he's always an agreeable performer, Pavarotti was not in
top vocal form Friday night, straining for notes when he should
have been caressing them. His big second-act aria, ``Una furtiva
lagrima,'' drew the usual feverish ovation from his fans, but in
truth it was only moderately soothing to the ear.
   Miss Battle, as the heroine Adina, took a while to warm up, at
first sounding oddly detached as she has in other recent
assignments at the Met. But after the intermission, she became more
animated and produced a rich, full tone along with her famous
silvery high notes.
   It was good to hear Doctor Dulcamara, the traveling quack who
arrives in a balloon, sung with the firm, booming voice that bass
Paul Plishka displayed. Often the part is given to an aging singer
who must rely on comic business to cover up an inability to get all
the notes across.
   Less effective was Leo Nucci as Sergeant Belcore, Nemorino's
rival for the love of Adina. His modest baritone just couldn't hold
its own in such high-powered vocal company.
   Marcello Panni, who conducted Pavarotti and Miss Battle in the
same opera in Central Park last summer, was making his house debut
and didn't quite have his act together. The orchestra sounded
ragged at times, and the singers, especially Pavarotti, tended to
go their own way where tempos were concerned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890422-0071 </DOCNO>
