<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Military     04-22 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Military,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Military Aircraft to Carry Civilian Cargoes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of military aircraft will be diverted to
civilian duty to haul 50,000 tons of farm produce, construction
equipment, and other goods around the country this year, an
official report said.
   The report Friday by the Tass news agency gave no reason for the
move. However, it said the military planes would be transporting
southern fruit and vegetables to northern cities, including Moscow
and Leningrad. Those cities suffer chronic shortages of such goods.
   
   Military aircraft have occasionally been used for civilian duty
in the past. They helped deliver equipment and relief workers after
the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear accident and the Armenian earthquake in
December, Tass said.
   A new resolution ordering the aircraft to carry civilian cargoes
was adopted by the Council of Ministers, the news agency said.
   Tass said the 60 military transport planes in the program will
include the Ruslan and Antheus jumbo jets, Il-76 turbojets and
An-12 turboprops. It did not say when the program would begin or
how long it would last.
   It said the jumbo jets ``are capable of bringing practically to
any point in the country large structural elements, building and
earth-moving machinery, cranes, excavators and transport vehicles.''
   Col. Gen. Vyacheslav Yefanov, chief of the military transport
division, was quoted by Tass as saying combat readiness will not be
impaired.
   ``Crews will continue to upgrade their flying skills, improve
maintenance of aircraft and will master radio communications,''
Yefanov said.
</TEXT>
