<DOCNO> AP890422-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Soviet     04-22 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Soviet,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official in Town to Work on Summit Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet deputy foreign minister arrived in
Beijing on Saturday for talks aimed at overcoming problems facing
the first Soviet-Chinese summit in 30 years, sources said.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is scheduled to come to
China on May 15.
   The two sides have had difficulty agreeing on a joint communique
to be issued at the visit's end, said an Eastern European source,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   It is hoped the visit by Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev
of the Soviet Union will clear up these difficulties, specifically
the Soviet and Chinese position on Vietnam and the war in Cambodia.
   Other difficulties concern the vision that each nation has of
future Sino-Soviet ties. Beijing has played down the significance
of its growing ties with Moscow, while the Soviets like to portray
their improving rapport with the Chinese as a foreign relations
coup.
   One indication of this occurred when the date of Gorbachev's
visit was announced in February. Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze ended a visit to China on Feb. 3 by announcing the
date. At a press conference that same day, a Chinese official
denied a date had been set.
   China then waited two days to announce that the date was May 15.
   Rogachev arrived Saturday afternoon, a Chinese source said. His
visit had been planned for some time but postponed for unknown
reasons.
   Both China and the Soviet Union support a Vietnamese troop
pullout from Cambodia by September. They also support an end to
Chinese aid for Cambodia's anti-Vietnamese guerrillas.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 to replace the pro-Chinese
Khmer Rouge with a pro-Vietnamese puppet government.
   China and the Soviet Union apparently still differ on the
composition of a transitional government, which would rule until
elections to replace the current Vietnamese-installed government.
   The last Soviet leader to visit Beijing was Nikita Khrushchev in
1959.
</TEXT>
