<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     04-22 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official: Elimination Of Nuclear Rockets In Germany Should Not Be
Excluded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking government official
said Saturday NATO should not exclude the possibility of
eliminating short-range nuclear rockets now based on German soil.
   The remark by Education Minister Juergen Moellemann could
further fuel a simmering disagreement between West Germany and the
United States over short-range nuclear weapons.
   West Germany is expected to press the United States to agree to
early superpower talks on reducing those weapons.
   Both the United States and Britain are strongly opposed to early
talks, contending that Warsaw Pact superiority in conventional
weapons requires a Western nuclear deterrent of short-range
arsenals.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl also wants the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization to postpone a decision on modernizing those weapons
until 1991 or 1992.
   Speaking at a meeting of the Free Democratic Party in Duisburg,
Moellemann reiterated the West German government's position but
went even farther, saying NATO and the Warsaw Pact should not
exclude the possibility of eliminating short-range nuclear weapons.
   Moellemann is a leading member of the Free Democrats, junior
partners in Kohl's coalition government.
   ``Depending on (disarmament) negotiations results and other
concrete realities, it should be decided after 1992 whether we need
any nuclear, land-based short-range rockets,'' Moellemann said.
   Moellemann also called on NATO to make its own ``wide-ranging''
disarmament initiatives and not to react only when the East bloc
makes disarmament proposals.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher and Defense
Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg are scheduled to fly to Washington on
Monday for talks with U.S. officials.
   They are expected to press the United States for negotiations
with the Soviets on reducing the number of short-range Lance
weapons, which have a range of about 60 miles and are mostly based
in West Germany.
</TEXT>
