<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     04-22 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Offers Amnesty to Tribal Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad on
Saturday offered amnesty to tribal rebels fighting for autonomy in
southern Bangladesh if they surrendered arms within a month, an
official said.
   Ershad made the offer while addressing a public meeting at the
town of Khagrachari, 110 miles southeast of Dhaka, the president's
press secretary, Toab Khan, said.
   Ershad also offered the rebels limited autonomy within the
country's constitution and promised to hold elections in the tribal
region, Khan said.
   The president said all rebels who surrender arms by May 20 will
be given amnesty and offered financial help.
   The tribal rebels, who have been blamed for about 4,000 killings
in their 14-year-old bush war, rejected an offer of limited
autonomy last year.
   The rebels are mostly Buddhist and oppose the government's
policy of settling Moslem Bengali people from central Bangladesh in
their region, the Chittagong hill tracts.
   The tracts encompass 8,125 square miles of hilly jungles on the
border with India.
</TEXT>
