<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     04-22 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Report No Progress on Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq resumed
direct peace talks Saturday, but they appeared no closer to a
permanent truce than when negotiations began eight months ago.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz, leaving after 2{ hours of
talks with his Iranian counterpart, Ali Akbar Velayati, said the
meeting brought only a reiteration of clashing positions.
   Asked if there was any progress on clearing those obstacles,
Aziz replied, ``I cannot say yes.''
   The talks were chaired by U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar, who also had two separate session in the past 24 hours
with the Iranian minister in an apparent attempt to soften
positions.
   Another session was planned Sunday, U.N. spokeswoman Nadia
Younes said.
   Periodic U.N.-sponsored talks began five days after an Aug. 20
cease-fire but immediately stalled over Iran's demand for a full
withdrawal of Iraqi troops from Iran and Iraq's insistence on early
dredging of the Shatt-al-Arab, its only sea outlet.
   The latest sessions started Thursday with a joint ministerial
meeting that Perez de Cuellar said did not deal with substantive
issues.
   Talks are tentatively scheduled to recess Monday, but
participants have left open the possibility of an extension.
   The president of the International Committee of the Red Cross,
Cornelio Sommaruga, said he met Perez de Cuellar Saturday and
expressed renewed concern that all prisoners of war taken in the
Iran-Iraq war must be repatriated.
   He said priority should continue to be given to wounded and sick
POWs, but also to captured children and the longest-held prisoners.
   The Geneva-based ICRC monitors compliance with the Geneva
Conventions on international humanitarian law.
   The ICRC agreed to supervise a POW exchange last November, but
Iran quickly pulled out of the accord after charging Iraq had
reneged.
   Only about 700 prisoners, mostly Iranians, have returned home
since the cease-fire took effect. The ICRC says both sides together
hold about 100,000 POWs captured in the eight-year war.
</TEXT>
