<FIRST>r a AM-DorranceWill     04-22 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dorrance Will,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Campbell Soup Heir Eliminated Trust For Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. heir John T. Dorrance Jr.
rewrote his will last year after a tax law was changed, eliminating
a trust that could have brought millions to the Philadelphia Museum
of Art and Princeton University.
   The trust was in a 1987 will but was deleted in a will dated
June 1988, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported Saturday.
   Dorrance, the biggest shareholder and former chairman of the
Camden, N.J., company, died of a heart attack April 9 at age 70.
His father invented condensed soup.
   Under the previous will, income from a trust would have
benefited the museum, Princeton and St. George's School, a prep
school in Newport, R.I., the newspaper reported. Income from the
trust would have continued for 25 years.
   The trust would have gotten the bulk of Dorrance's estate, the
newspaper said, but did not elaborate. Dorrance often was included
in lists of the nation's richest people with a fortune estimated at
$1.5 billion.
   Under the new will, Dorrance left nothing to the two schools,
both of which he had attended, the newspaper said. The museum will
get two valuable pieces of porcelain as well as $5 million that
Dorrance had pledged before his death.
   Most of the estate will be divided equally among his six
grandchildren. Its value was not specified in the will.
   Campbell spokesman Scott Rombach said Saturday he could not
confirm that a will had been filed or give details of any previous
will.
   Sandra Horrocks, a spokeswoman for the museum, said Saturday she
would have no comment. Princeton spokeswoman Jacquelyn Savani did
not immediately return a telephone message Saturday seeking comment.
   His will was changed after Congress revoked a
``generation-skipping'' estate tax break offered to grandchildren
of wealthy people who form large trusts that provide income to
charities, the newspaper said. Charitable groups had lobbied
Congress not to revise the tax break, arguing it would lead to
fewer gifts.
   Princeton would have received 50 percent of the income from the
trust, the museum 40 percent and St. George's 10 percent, the
newspaper said.
   Dorrance was chairman of the art museum board. His $5 million
pledge was the biggest cash gift the museum had ever received.
   ``We are thankful for his vast generosity given during his
lifetime,'' said Joseph Rishel, museum curator of 19th-century art.
   The value of the two pieces of porcelain _ nearly life-size
goats made of Meissen china in the early 18th century _ has not
been disclosed, but Rishel said the figures are ``fabulous, really
spectacular, real showstoppers.''
</TEXT>
