<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   04-22 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0561,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Blocks Israelis Trying To Show Support For Nahalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Arab stabbed, army confirming
five wounded; CORRECTS to five dead, sted six; picks up 12th pvs: In the...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army on Saturday barred Israeli leftists
carrying black flags of mourning from entering the West Bank
village of Nahalin, the site of a bloody raid by border police that
killed five people.
   Also Saturday, officials at Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital said a
Palestinian suspected of collaborating with Israeli authorities had
died Thursday of stab wounds.
   Arab reports identified the man as Musallam Mahmoud Shaheen, 40,
and said masked youths broke into his West Bank home and attacked
him because they suspected him of cooperating with Israel.
   Another suspected collaborator, a 32-year-old Palestinian woman,
was hospitalized with broken limbs after being beaten for at least
two days by Arab militants, the army and Arab reports said.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, 16 Palestinians,
including six children under the age of 15, were wounded in clashes
with troops, Arab hospital officials said. An army official
confirmed five wounded.
   Throughout the occupied lands, Palestinians observed a general
strike called by the pro-PLO leaders of the uprising.
   Shops were shuttered and transportation came to a halt. In Gaza,
activists blocked roads with stones to enforce the strike.
   Israeli legislator Yossi Sarid led a convoy of 20 cars draped
with black flags to Nahalin, but the group was stopped by troops
slightly more than a mile outside the village. Sarid said soldiers
told him the area was closed to civilians.
   ``It's possible to block our entrance, but they can't block our
message of total opposition to the massacre that happened in the
village,'' Sarid of the left-wing Citizens Rights Movement told The
Associated Press.
   Preliminary results of an army investigation showed that border
police fired indiscriminately during their April 13
search-and-arrest raid in the village. In the occupied territories,
border police are under army command and are often dispatched on
such raids.
   At Mukassed Hospital, 25-year-old Walid Mohammed Najadereh died
late Friday of head wounds sustained in the raid, hospital
officials said. His death brought the death toll in the raid to
five.
   The deaths of Najadereh and Shaheen raised to 442 the number of
Palestinians killed since the December 1987 start of the uprising.
Eighteen Israelis also died.
   In the West Bank town of Ramallah, 32-year-old Sabah Kanaan was
hospitalized with multiple fractures after being held by members of
a so-called Palestinian strike force, army officials and Arab
reporters said.
   The militants broke into Mrs. Kanaan's home in the West Bank
city of Nablus on Tuesday night and beat her with clubs and sticks
because they believed she collaborated with Israel, said an Arab
reporter, quoting the woman's neighbors.
   ``She was shouting `I'll stop, I'll stop!''' the reporter quoted
the neighbors as saying.
   Israel radio said Mrs. Kanaan was held for three days.
   Since the start of the uprising, dozens of Palestinians,
including several women, have been killed by fellow Palestinians
who accused them of collaboration.
</TEXT>
