<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Explosion     04-22 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Explosion,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion in Moscow Watch Factory Touches Off Disaster Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire and explosion in a Moscow watch factory
killed two people, injured two others and touched off rumors that a
radioactive cloud had been released over the Soviet capital,
official media said Saturday.
   However, the Tass news agency said the worries were based on
``incredible and unfounded'' rumors.
   Tass said the Moscow city council was besieged with telephone
calls Friday night from Muscovites worried that their neighborhood
might be contaminated by poisonous gas released by the explosion
earlier in the day.
   State-run Radio Moscow said some Muscovites were concerned that
radiation might have leaked into the air.
   Tass, in dismissing the worries, said authorities were trying to
determine who called child-care centers to tell them to keep
children indoors and close windows.
   The fire and explosion occurred when plant workers installing
new wiring in an unventilated area accidentally ignited a gas leak,
Tass said.
   The blast killed a woman worker, and an electrician was burned
and later died. Two other women were hospitalized with injuries.
   ``Troubled Muscovites were inquiring as to what kind of
explosion happened Friday morning at one of the enterprises of the
Cheremyshkinsky region and how dangerous it was for people living
in neighboring areas,'' Tass said.
</TEXT>
