<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1632EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Georgia     04-22 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Paper Identifies Chemical Used in Georgia, Says it Not Fatal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry newspaper said Saturday that
an irritating chemical agent was used on pro-independence
demonstrators in Soviet Georgia, but it quoted an official as
saying the substance does not cause suffocation or poisoning.
   However, the newspaper acknowledged a report in the local
Communist Party daily, Zarya Vostoka, that 61 people suffering
poisoning symptoms were hospitalized in Georgia and that some were
in ``grave condition.''
   Georgian activists claim several of the 19 people killed when
soldiers broke up an April 9 demonstration were victims of poison
gas. They also say military authorities refused to identify the
substance or tell doctors how to treat patients suffering from
exposure to it.
   The Defense Ministry paper Red Star identified the substance as
``cheremukha.''
   Soviet officials have previously said ``tear gas'' was used in
Georgia but have given no further details.
   ``We used only `cheremukha,' and it alone,'' Red Star quoted a
representative of the Soviet Interior Ministry, Maj.-Gen. Yu.
Yefimov, as saying. ``It is a substance basically consisting of
chloroacetophenone.... `Cheremukha' is an irritant, but it does not
cause suffocation or poisoning.''
   A Western military attache in Moscow said the substance's base
was a type of incapacitating agent stronger than tear gas and akin
to what is commonly known in the West as ``CS.''
   Yefimov told the newspaper only 27 cartridges of the substance
were used by soldiers, ``and not in the square in front of
Government House where people were killed, but in two other
places'' on the capital city's main thoroughfare, Rustaveli
Prospekt.
   He said internal security troops attached to the Interior
Ministry used the chemical on his order, ``as they say, when
passions `had burst their banks.'''
   Despite Yefimov's contention the chemical cannot cause poisoning
or suffocation, the weekly Moscow News reported in its issue last
week that the substance used on protesters could have been a factor
in the fatalities.
   ``The use of gas in great concentrations can lead to the
instantaneous loss of consciousness,'' Moscow News said. ``A
helpless person then falls under the feet of a running crowd.''
   Yefimov said the use of the chemical was authorized by a July 28
decree from the Supreme Soviet Presidium, which says ``special
means'' may be used for ``suppressing mass unrest, group violations
of public order and other anti-social activities.''
   He claimed the April 9 rally in front of Georgian government
headquarters fell into that category because ``seizure of political
power, overthrow of the present regime and the separation of
Georgia from the U.S.S.R. were publicly discussed.''
   Georgia's leadership assumed responsibility for the clash and
the Communist Party leader and premier resigned.
   The protests began in early April in reaction to demands by the
small Black Sea area of Abkhazia to be separated from Georgia. They
evolved into massive protests by groups depending Georgian
independence from the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
