<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela     04-22 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Chief Calls Nationwide Strike For May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the nation's biggest union
said Saturday he will call a strike next month to protest
government austerity measures that earlier this year prompted the
worst rioting in Venezuelan history.
   The one-day strike, which would be the first major work stoppage
in 31 years of democratic government, ``will definitely go'' in
May, said Juan Jose Delpino, president of the Venezuelan Workers
Confederation.
   The union plans to hold a two-day congress next week to discuss
strategy for fighting the belt-tightening program, which resulted
in sharp increases in bus fares, gasoline and other goods and
services.
   The austerity plan, the result of an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund so Venezuela could ease its $33 billion
foreign debt, spurred violent protests in February. More than 300
people were killed and 2,000 injured in Caracas alone.
   The labor group represents 3 million of Venezuela's 5.8 million
workers.
   President Carlos Andres Perez called the threatened strike
``suicide, because nobody would join it.''
   ``The strike and the massive obedience to our call will be the
response to that claim,'' Delpino said.
   Venezuela, an oil-producing nation whose economy has collapsed
as petroleum prices have plunged, had experienced little labor
unrest before February's riots.
   ``Venezuelan workers are living through the worst crisis since
the (labor group) was created,'' Delpino told The Associated Press.
``Workers have felt the severe impact of the economic policy.''
   The austerity program eliminated subisides on more than 25 basic
food products and implemented an indexing system that tied wage
increases to inflation rates.
   Despite the friction between the union and the government, Perez
is to open Monday's labor congress.
</TEXT>
