<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     04-22 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Report Says Israel Expels 60 Families From South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese newspaper said Saturday that
Israel has expelled 60 families from their farms in southern
Lebanon after they refused to sell the army their land.
   An Israeli army official in Jerusalem called the reports ``not
true, totally unfounded.'' In southern Lebanon, the spokesman for
the U.N. peacekeeping force said he had no reports of villagers
being expelled. Lebanese police could not immediately confirm the
report.
   The daily An-Nahar said a 500-strong Israeli force backed by 30
armored personnel carriers stormed seven farms around the town of
Shibaa Friday and rounded up 300 people.
   Shibaa lies within Israel's self-declared security zone, a
six-to-10-mile-deep strip patrolled by Israeli troops and
Israeli-backed militiamen.
   ``The commander told the farmers they have either to sell their
10-square-mile land to Israel or give it up,'' An-Nahar said.
   It quoted unidentified residents as saying the Israelis opened
fire to force the farmers out, but that no casualties were reported.
   The farmers loaded their belongings on 300 mules and left for
Shibaa, along with their 30,000 goats and 500 cows, An-Nahar said.
   Timor Goksel, the spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon said: ``We received a petition from the village signed by
142 people. They said they were informed (by Israel) that their
land would be confiscated for military purposes.''
   ``Some villagers have said they have been offered compensation,
but most don't want to accept it,'' Goksel said.
   He said the U.N. force began investigating the reports after the
Lebanese government filed a complaint with the United Nations.
   Israel expelled 70 Lebanese civilians from Shibaa and several
villages in the security zone earlier this year for refusing to
cooperate with the area's Israeli-sponsored local administration.
   Israel carved out its security zone when it withdrew the bulk of
its occupation army from southern Lebanon in June 1985.
   The strip, which extends from the Mediterranean coast in the
west to the foothills of Mount Hermon in the east, serves as a
buffer against cross-border guerrilla attacks against northern
Israeli settlements.
</TEXT>
