<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     04-22 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says Former Party Leader Kadar in Poor Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Janos Kadar, removed in May as head of
Hungary's Communist Party after 32 years in power, is unable to
carry out his official functions because of poor health, a
government minister said Saturday.
   Kadar, 76, was replaced by Karoly Grosz as party leader at a
special conference and given the honorary post of party president.
   Kadar attended the second half of a meeting of the Communist
Party Central Committee last month but has been absent from recent
party meetings.
   Minister of State Rezso Nyers told a meeting of reform
communists Saturday in Szolnok that Kadar's attendance at the
Central Committee meeting may have been ``his last such
appearance,'' the official MTI news agency reported.
   Kadar was ousted as party chief as reform Communists accused him
of stifling progress. They claimed he halted Hungary's economic and
political reforms in the 1970s and crticized his role in backing
the Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968 that crushed that
nation's ``Prague Spring'' reforms.
   MTI reported Nyers said the more than three decades of Kadar's
rule should be reviewed but Kadar probably would not become
personally involved in any such review because of his health.
   In another development, a fourth man who had been invited to
rejoin the Communist Party after being expelled a year ago will
remain outside the party, according to a broadcast on Hungary radio.
   It reported Mihaly Bihari, a political scientist and reform
communist, said there were ``incompatible differences'' between the
Central Committee and the four expelled last April.
   The three others, economist Laszlo Lengyel, historian Zoltan
Biro and parliamentary deputy Zoltan Kiraly, announced earlier last
week that they would not rejoin the party.
   The Central Control Committee, the party's top disciplinary
body, had reversed its expulsion order at a meeting Monday.
   Bihari was quoted by Hungary radio as saying the party is
paralyzed by irreconcilable differences within its own ranks. There
has been discussion in recent weeks about a possible split between
the party's reform and orthodox wings.
</TEXT>
