<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Solidarity     04-22 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Comes out of Trenches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity activists are scouting for
offices, hooking up telephones and signing up volunteer poll
watchers in a flurry of activity after regaining legal status for
their independent labor movement.
   Near the center of Warsaw, a former history institute is being
transformed into the Solidarity Citizens Committee's national
election headquarters. At another location, a small union press
office has opened. At a third spot, opposition editors are planning
to put out a newspaper.
   Solidarity volunteers _ university students, mothers on leave
from jobs, longtime activists and others _ are struggling with
typical Polish shortages of office supplies, furniture and phone
lines. But they no longer need look over their shoulders.
   The government crushed Solidarity, the first independent union
in the East bloc, during a martial law crackdown in 1981 and later
banned it. After years of illegal activity, Solidarity recaptured
its legal status when a government-controlled court lifted the ban
Monday.
   The legalization stemmed from talks between the opposition and
the government that concluded in an agreement April 5. The
government also agreed to free elections to a new chamber of
parliament and other electoral reforms in exchange for political
and economic cooperation from Solidarity.
   Before it was suppressed, Solidarity claimed 10 million members.
   However, speaking at the end of a three-day visit to Italy,
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa predicted Saturday in Rome that his
labor movement will dwindle as it gives rise to splinter groups
during the reforms in Poland.
   ``From Solidarity, other economic and political organizations
will be born,'' said Walesa. ``Solidarity for the moment is huge,
but it will become smaller with the growth of other organizations.
This is the logical course of events.''
   The first major office to open in Warsaw since legalization was
the Solidarity Citizens Committee headquarters in an empty former
history institute on the edge of the picturesque Saxon Garden park.
The organization, technically separate from Solidarity, is racing
against early deadlines for finding candidates. It is collecting
nominating signatures, running campaigns, and training election
observers for parliamentary voting scheduled for June 4 and June 18.
   On Friday, Jacek Kuron, a veteran activist slated to run for the
existing upper chamber of parliament, scrambled through the
building holding quick chats with several prominent activists in
the bustling center.
   ``It's full of problems,'' he replied when asked about the
practical side of ushering in legal activity. ``We don't have
telephones, we don't have space, we don't have anything _ but we
will.''
   Jan Litynski, spokesman for the Warsaw regional chapter of
Solidarity, said: ``The mood is getting hotter and hotter because
of the elections.''
   Anatol Lawina, a Solidarity representative to the State Election
Commission, said he hopes to line up 100,000 people nationwide to
help guard against cheating at the 22,000 polling sites.
   Elsewhere in the country, local election offices and news
bureaus were also being opened.
   The Election Newspaper, a newspaper that expects to circulate
500,000 copies, has found offices in an empty building in central
Warsaw, said Ernest Skalski, one of the editors.
   The paper will become the first opposition mass-circulation
daily in the East bloc with its first edition, scheduled for May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
