<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-22 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms, Hail and High Winds Hit Minnesota and Iowa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hail and damaging winds hit parts of Minnesota and Iowa on
Saturday along with the first thunderstorms of spring, while widely
scattered showers dampened parts of Florida and the northwestern
states.
   High winds in north-central Iowa damaged buildings and downed
power lines in Swea City and Bancroft and uprooted trees elsewhere.
   Hail hit near Bancroft and in southwestern Minnesota where high
winds blew down a barn north of Windom.
   A cold front in the Northeast, meanwhile, left four inches of
snow in Caribou, Maine, by early afternoon and 2 inches at Mount
Washington, N.H.
   A few showers and thunderstorms were over the southeast and east
central coast of Florida. There were widely scattered rainshowers
over the northwestern states.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with sunny
skies from the southern and central high Plains to the South.
   Temperatures were generally in the 80s early Saturday afternoon
from the southeastern states to the southern and central high
Plains with readings in the 90s reported in eastern parts of
Colorado, New Mexico and Nebraska.
   Cool weather prevailed in the Great Lakes region and northeast
where readings were mostly in the 40s and 50s early Saturday
afternoon. Temperatures were in the 30s across northern New England
and much of eastern New York state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 26
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 96 degrees at Dodge City, Kan., and
Lubbock and Wink, Texas.
   The low for the nation was 22 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Sunday called for some showers and
thunderstorms over the south central United States and scattered
showers and thunderstorms in the upper Ohio Valley, the southern
Appalachians and from the middle and upper Mississippi Valley to
the lower Great Lakes; rain from Michigan through Indiana and
western Ohio to western North Carolina and western Virginia; snow
showers over northern and central Maine; and scattered rainshowers
from the northern and central Pacific Coast to Montana with rain
likely across Oregon, Northern California and southwestern Idaho.
Sunny skies were expected across most of the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were expected to remain below 60 from the Great
Lakes region to New Jersey and New England with highs in the 40s in
New England and eastern New York state, and in the 50s from the
northern and central Pacific Coast to western Montana; and above 80
from Florida and Georgia through the lower and middle Mississippi
Valley to the southern and central high Plains, with highs in the
90s from central and western Texas to southeastern Nebraska.
Readings were expected in the 80s and 90s in the Southwestern
deserts.
</TEXT>
