<FIRST>r i AM-Portugal-Police     04-22 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Portugal-Police,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Condemns Extremists in Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva on
Saturday blamed extreme leftists for prompting demands by police
officers to form a union, news reports said. The demands provoked
violent clashes within the police force.
   Six policemen were arrested in the clashes Friday between riot
police and fellow officers demanding union rights. They were
released Saturday pending trial. About 100 uniformed officers
greeted the release with victory signs and calls for further
protest.
   Riot police used water cannons, dogs and batons Friday against
protesting officers outside the Internal Affairs Ministry.
   As the riot escalated, civilians joined demonstrators in hurling
stones at the riot squad. Seventeen people were reported injured.
   ``Extremist forces, communist forces and some socialists were
behind the movements in the Public Security Police,'' Silva was
quoted by the national Lusa news agency as saying.
   Cavaco Silva's center-right Social Democratic government has not
granted union rights to uniformed police units, saying their
militarized status makes trade unions unconstitutional.
   Portugal's two major trade union federations, the
Communist-inspired General Confederation of Portuguese Workers and
the Socialist-led General Workers Union, called for a demonstration
Monday to protest the actions of the riot police.
   General Workers Union General Secretary Jose Torres Couto, also
a Socialist deputy in the National Assembly, said he would ask for
a parliamentary inquiry into Friday's riot and demanded the
resignation of Internal Affairs Minister Jose Antonio da Silveira
Godinho.
</TEXT>
