<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaSpill     04-22 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Spill,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cleanup of Waste Water Continues From Louisiana Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAYOU SORREL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four pumps were used to empty the
remaining oil-tainted water from a disabled, leaking barge Saturday
and workers laid out absorbent pads to clean up the impurities that
spilled into Grand River.
   Officials said 10,000 gallons of the non-hazardous waste
material _ water with small percentages of oil and alcohol _
spilled into the river early Friday on a loading dock on the river
about 35 miles southwest of Baton Rouge.
   Earlier estimates had put the amount of the spill at 100,000
gallons or more.
   ``As of 10 a.m., they were pumping out the barge into vacuum
trucks,'' said Douglas Wootten, a marine science technician for the
Coast Guard. ``They were one behind another. As soon as one is
filled, another pulls up.''
   The spill occurred when a barge carrying 900,000 gallons of the
waste water from an Exxon plant in Houston buckled in the middle
while workers unloaded the waste into tanker trucks.
   There were initial fears for the fragile environment _ the site
of the spill is near a large marshland area _ and some fish died.
But authorities said the spill was quickly contained by booms and
the environmental damage would be minimal.
   ``They have booms in place and only a small amount of the
product went down river. It is being retrieved,'' Wootten said.
Absorbent pads have been put out to soak up the impurities in the
river, officials said.
   Gordon Vice, an employee at GSX Land Treatment, which was being
paid to dispose of the waste water, did not have the required
Merchant Marine certification for performing the work at the time
of the accident, said Coast Guard Chief Warrant Officer Larry Doss.
GSX is assuming responsibility for the cleanup, officials said.
   GSX spokesman Bobby Mayweather said Saturday afternoon that Vice
was at the site and unavailable for comment. A woman answering the
telephone at Vice's home in White Castle also said he was
unavailable.
   Exxon, which has been harshly criticized in the past month
because of the 10 million-gallon spill from an oil tanker that hit
a reef off Alaska, had no involvement in Friday's spill except that
one of its plants was the source of the waste water, officials said.
   ``Exxon is getting a bad rap on this,'' Wootten said. ``They had
nothing to do with the spill. They had just hired a company to haul
the product off. In fact, Exxon should be commended _ they have no
liability and they still sent a clean-up crew.''
   Wootten said the amount of the so-called ``slop water'' leaking
from the barge into the Grand River was very small.
   ``Drip, drip, drip, that's all it is,'' he said.
   Paul Dubois, a spokesman for the Palmer Co., owner of the barge,
said the water-alcohol mixture is used to wash out tanks and ships.
When it's dirty with oil residue, it becomes waste water, he said.
   Exxon estimated the water contained 3 percent oil and 7 percent
alcohol. The alcohol began evaporating after the spill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
