<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1851EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AstroTurfAnniversary     04-22 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AstroTurf Anniversary,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artificial Grass Celebrates First 25 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AstroTurf, the synthetic sod that makes
it possible to play football, baseball and other sports where grass
doesn't grow, had a 25th birthday party at the private school where
it all began.
   AstroTurf's silver anniversary was observed Friday at Moses
Brown School, the Quaker school where the prototype was installed
25 years ago as part of an effort to help city kids become more
physically fit.
   ``We had an idea that it would develop into something big,''
recalled the school's athletic director and football coach, Jerry
A. Zeoli, who oversaw the installation and was among the 20 to 30
people at Friday's celebration.
   AstroTurf has been installed in more than 500 locations in 32
countries, said AstroTurf Industries Inc. President Ed M. Milner.
   It wound up at Moses Brown because of a Ford Foundation study
showing urban children were less fit than their suburban
counterparts. In 1964, the foundation gave the school a grant to
test the artificial grass in its new field house.
   In developing the turf, Monsanto Co. studied traction, shock
absorbance, weather resistance, how balls rolled and bounced, and a
host of other factors, Milner said in a statement.
   Moses Brown used its nylon field for baseball, tennis, soccer
and lacrosse, Zeoli said. It also saw service in graduation
ceremonies and dances.
   ``You can clean it so easily, all you need is a vacuum
cleaner,'' Zeoli said.
   Zeoli figured AstroTurf might have some potential when in 1965
some officials from the Houston Astrodome journeyed north to have a
look at the nylon carpet because they just couldn't get real grass
to grow in their new domed stadium.
   The Texans decided on an improved version, and the synthetic
turf was subsequently named for the Astrodome. Artificial turf,
which costs less to maintain than the natural variety, is used
today in most professional football stadiums.
   AstroTurf is made from a nylon polymer, which is dyed green and
spun into a ribbon, then crimped to give it texture and knitted to
a tough backing.
   Moses Brown's prototype was far different from today's
AstroTurf, Zeoli said. Its backing was just one-sixteenth of an
inch thick, compared to as much as an inch today.
   ``I could run plays and it was ideal, but I couldn't
scrimmage,'' Zeoli recalled. ``Hitting the surface could probably
injure someone.''
   Some professional athletes have blamed injuries on AstroTurf,
saying the synthetic surface does not give the way natural turf
does.
   However, AstroTurf Industries' magazine, Turf Talk, quotes
several doctors as saying the product does not increase the risk of
football injuries.
   AstroTurf Industries was a subsidiary of Monsanto until February
1988, when it was sold to the West German company Balsam
Sportstattenbau of Steinhagen. The company remains based in Dalton,
Ga.
   As an anniversary gift, the company resurfaced the weight room
at Moses Brown with AstroTurf.
   Its old AstroTurf is still going strong. Three-fourths of the
prototype still covers the field house floor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890422-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSStudy     04-22 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Study,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot AIDS Study A Success, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People responded with surprising frankness to
questions about sexual habits and drug use in a pilot study to
determine the prevalence of AIDS, suggesting a similar study could
succeed nationwide, U.S. health officials say.
   Of the 308 eligible residents approached in January and February
at their homes in Allegheny County, 263 _ or 85 percent _ agreed to
fill out a form containing questions about sexual habits and drug
use and to give a blood sample for the study, in exchange for $50.
   ``I'd call it a surprising success,'' said Peter Hurley, project
officer for the Atlanta-based Centers for Disease Control, which
commissioned the survey.
   The results were discussed Friday at a meeting of the Allegheny
County Health Department's Community Advisory Committee, which
approved the pilot study last fall.
   Still unanswered, researchers said, is whether people
participating in a survey are actually telling the truth about
their intimate habits, and whether a national survey could be done
at close to the original estimated cost of $25 million.
   Besides the Allegheny County study, a pilot survey is slated to
start this summer in Dallas. One in Washington, D.C., was scrapped
in August after community leaders complained it appeared to single
out blacks.
   The pilot studies are running about 20 percent over budget,
largely because of the effort required to quell community concern
about them, Hurley said.
   In Allegheny County, out of an original pool of 450 homes
randomly chosen for the survey, interviewers found 308 where a
person at home was aged between 18 and 54, the survey's target
ages. In all, 263 of the 308 people agreed to fill out a form and
give blood.
   Most residents said they agreed to take part because they wanted
to help research into acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Only 15
said the main reason was to get the $50 paid to everyone who
answered the 22 questions and gave a blood sample.
   AIDS tests were run on all of the blood samples, but county
health officials said they will not release the results. Even
survey participants were not given the results of their own blood
tests, but those worried about having been exposed to AIDS were
advised to contact their doctor or a health clinic.
</TEXT>
