<FIRST>u i AM-France-Missile     04-22 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Missile,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Militiamen, U.S. Businessman Arrested in Arms Delivery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Protestant militiamen from Northern Ireland
and an American businessman were arrested in the delivery of
missile-launcher parts to a South African diplomat, a government
official said Saturday.
   The French official said the three militiamen belong to the
Ulster Defense Association, the largest paramilitary organization
in Northern Ireland.
   The arrests were made Friday at a Paris hotel four men were
delivering spare parts for the British-made Blowpipe
shoulder-carried missile launcher to Daniel Storm, a South African
diplomat, the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said Storm, who is covered by diplomatic immunity, was
released but the other four were held for questioning at the
offices of the DST, France's counterespionage agency.
   There was no official announcement of the arrests.
   News reports identified the three militiamen as Noel Little, 40;
Samuel Quinn, 41; and James King, 50. The news agency Agence
France-Presse identified the American as 40-year-old Douglas
Bernhart.
   The agency said without providing details that Bernhart kept an
office in Geneva. However, his name was not listed in the Geneva
phone book or a local register of companies.
   French law permits police to hold suspects for questioning for
up to four days before they are charged with an offense.
   A duty officer at the Interior Ministry, which is responsible
for the counterespionage agency, said he could not comment on the
report.
   In Johannesburg, the Foreign Affairs department confirmed
Saturday that Storm was on the staff of the South African embassy
in Paris and said there would be an investigation of the case.
   The Paris newspaper Le Monde said it appeared the South Africans
hoped to copy the delivered parts to produce a similar
anti-aircraft missile of their own, possibly for export. It said
the spare parts apparently had been stolen but gave no details.
   None of the reports carried details of payments for the parts.
   In Belfast, a spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constablulary,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said a dummy Blowpipe missile
was stolen over the weekend of April 8-9 from a Territorial Army,
or national guard, base in Newtonards, County Down. He said the
security forces insist it had no working parts.
   There was no known evidence of a link between the discovery and
the arrests in France.
   The Blowpipe, sometimes compared to the U.S.-made Stinger
missile launcher, weighs about 45 pounds and fires 76mm guided
surface-to-air missiles.
</TEXT>
