<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras     04-22 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Capital Flight Damaging Honduras; Pleads For Money
Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo pleaded
Saturday with his countrymen to return their money to Honduras,
saying capital flight was crippling the economy.
   Azcona said more than $1 billion had left the country in the
last nine years, most of it deposited in U.S. banks.
   He blamed the capital flight on regional conflicts that plague
Central America.
   ``The uncertain panorama of Central America has badly damaged
Honduras, one of the few nations in the region which lives in
democracy and relative tranquility,'' Azcona said.
   There are no restrictions on the taking of capital out of
Honduras.
   Honduras is not involved in civil war, but neighbors such as El
Salvador, Guatemala and Nicaragua are, and Honduras has become a
haven for both refugees and guerrillas.
   Azcona said that the ``situation confronting the region provokes
fear and insecurity in local and foreign investors.''
   ``Because of this more than $1 billion has been deposited in
foreign bank accounts, specifically in the United States, by many
Hondurans in the last few years,'' he said.
   He said the majority of Honduran businessmen have bank accounts
in the United States of between $200,000 and $300,000.
   He spoke in an interview with Radio America, one of the main
networks in Honduras.
   ``If our compatriots would return only 25 percent of this
capital, which would be about $250 million, it would partially
solve the problems that confront Honduras,'' the president said.
   Honduras is ranked by many international organizations as one of
the poorest nations in the hemisphere. It suffers 30 percent
unemployment, a budget deficit of more than $300 million and an
inflation rate of 30 percent.
</TEXT>
