<FIRST>r a AM-TwinsReunited 1stLd-Writethru a0573 04-22 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Twins Reunited, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0573,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twins Reunite After 34-year Adoption Separation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with reunion, quotes, details.
Picks up 6th graf, ```Their father...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twins separated shortly after birth bridged more
than 30 years and 2,000 miles Saturday in the culmination of a
woman's decade-long search for the sister she never knew.
   Susan Muchlenbruch's efforts paid off last week when she finally
located her twin, Mary Ann McNew, living in a Seattle suburb. The
sisters met for the first time in nearly 35 years Saturday at
O'Hare International Airport.
   ``You don't know how happy we are,'' Ms. Muchlenbruch said,
crying and hugging her sister.
   ``We're going to catch up on all we've lost, all the years we've
missed together,'' said a tearful Ms. McNew. ``I had a feeling I
might have family out there, but I didn't know where.''
   The Rev. Earl Davis, of the nearby Wilmette Church of Christ,
said the congregation would pay for hotel accommodations for the
sisters for the weekend so they wouldn't have to stay in Ms.
Muchlenbruch's trailer home.
   ``This is probably the biggest thing that has ever happened in
(Ms. Muchlenbruch's) life,'' Davis said.
   Ms. McNew's adoptive mother, Gladys McNew, said her daughter was
``kind of a wreck for a whole week'' looking forward to the
three-day reunion at her sister's home in the Chicago suburb of
Northfield.
   ``She hasn't been able to eat, sleep or hardly work,'' Mrs.
McNew said in a telephone interview Saturday from Bellevue, Wash.
   The twins were born at Cook County Hospital almost 35 years ago.
Shortly afterward, their mother was institutionalized for emotional
problems, said Debbie Felt, supervisor of the missing persons
service for the Salvation Army, which helped Ms. Muchlenbruch with
her search after a decade of futile checking on her own.
   ``Their father tried to raise them on his own for the first
three months, couldn't handle it and had to put them up for
adoption,'' Ms. Felt said.
   Gladys McNew said she and her husband had wanted to adopt both
twins, but the Chicago adoption agency's policy was to divide twins.
   ``At that time, they did not want to put twins together ... and
they only gave us one,'' she said. ``I thought it was a cruel thing
to do.''
   For years, Mrs. McNew kept the secret from her daughter.
   ``Through the years I didn't say anything because I didn't want
her frustrated and looking for someone she couldn't find,'' she
said.
   When Mary turned 6, her family moved to Seattle.
   ``This one was a fluke case,'' said Ms. Felt. ``We didn't have
any leads except one, and we ended up sending just one letter.''
   The Salvation Army sent the letter to Ms. McNew, who is divorced
with a 14-year-old daughter.
   ``She waited all of two minutes before curiosity got the best of
her and she called her sister,'' Ms. Felt said.
   ``Every time I talk to them they're crying because they're so
happy,'' she said. ``They're so excited they can't think straight
anymore.''
</TEXT>
