<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela-Scandal     04-22 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Scandal,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Investigating Exchange Fraud Bars Two Ex-Ministers From Leaving
Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge investigating allegations of
foreign-exchange fraud has issued an order barring two former
finance ministers from leaving the country, newspapers reported
Saturday.
   Congressman Carlos Tablante, whose accusations brought about the
investigation, has said the case involves overbilling and grants
for dollars for non-existent imports that could amount to more than
$4 billion.
   The alleged fraud occurred during the administration of
President Jaime Lusinchi of the Social Democratic Party, when there
was a preferential dollar exchange system.
   That system was abolished shortly after the Feb. 2 inauguration
of President Carlos Andres Perez, also a Social Democrat, who
succeeded Lusinchi.
   The preferential plan pegged the exchange at 14.50 bolivars per
dollar for some imports and foreign debt payments. When it was
eliminated, it left only the free market rate that ranged around 36
bolivars per dollar last month.
   Judge Luis La Riva's order issued Friday banned ex-finance
ministers Manuel Azpurua and Hector Hurtado from leaving Venezuela.
Also named in the prohibition order were former vice finance
minister Jorge Garcia Duque; Egdalia Bastardo, who had been the
director of Recadi, and an unspecified number of other people who
the judge did not identify.
   Recadi was the government agency, since abolished, that for six
years was in charge of granting the preferential exchange for
imports. Investigations by both La Riva and a congressional
committee are centered on Recadi.
   Azpurua was finance minister during the first three years of
Lusinchi's five-year administration. He was replaced by Hurtado,
who had previously served as minister of development.
</TEXT>
