<FIRST>r i AM-GoldfishRescue     04-22 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Goldfish Rescue,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>The One That Got Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCARBOROUGH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A goldfish was reunited with its
owner Saturday after a week few goldfish can claim to have survived.
   The six-inch red fantail suffered a close brush with death a
week ago when it fell from a motorcycle rider's knapsack onto a
busy highway, but was rescued by a passing motorist and
resuscitated at a nearby garage.
   Denise Warley, who was traveling in the opposite direction from
the motorcyclist, saw the newly purchased fish in its plastic bag
of water pop onto the Scalby Road in this seaside town on the
northeast coast of England.
   Mrs. Warley, 43, asked her husband to stop their car and ran
back along the road as cars drove over the bag and burst it,
leaving the goldfish high and dry.
   The fish slithered into the gutter and was gasping its last when
Mrs. Warley scooped it up in her hands, sprinted to a nearby garage
and plunged it into water from a watering can. Then the Warleys
took it home to share a tank with their own goldfish.
   ``When I picked him out of the gutter he looked in a state of
shock,'' the good Samaritan said. ``No wonder _ talk about the one
that got away, he must have more lives than a cat.''
   The story of the rescue appeared in a local newspaper and a pet
shop owner recognized the fish he had sold. By a stroke of luck,
the purchaser had left his name and address at the shop earlier
when he bought a puppy there.
   So after a week few of its peers would envy, the lucky red
fantail was safely handed over to his owner.
</TEXT>
