<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0566 04-22 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0566,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaskans Plan Five Minutes of Silence to Remember Untarnished Coastline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Coast Guard saying
two Navy ships would join cleanup as floating hotels. Picks up 3rd graf,
`Gov. Steve...' SUBS 13th graf, `The 425-foot...,' to UPDATE with Soviet
ship skimming 10,000 gallons by midday.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor on Saturday asked Alaskans to
observe five minutes of silence Sunday in remembrance of the way
things were before the Exxon Valdez oil spill fouled hundreds of
miles of pristine coastline.
   The Coast Guard and hundreds of volunteers, meanwhile, scrubbed
tar-like oil from beaches. Vice Admiral Clyde Robbins, the Coast
Guard's on-scene coordinator, said the USS Juneau and USS Fort
McHenry would join the effort as floating hotels.
   ``They (Exxon) asked me for them, subject to finding out what
the price is. I suspect they'll use them,'' said Robbins, adding
that he had been told the ships cost the U.S. government $150,000 a
day to operate.
   Exxon has asked to pay only the amount exceeding the
government's cost of operating the landing ships, which are both
based in San Diego, Robbins said. The cost issue will be settled at
the ``highest levels'' of government, he said.
   The Juneau, due in Valdez on Monday, can sleep 840 troops. The
Fort McHenry can sleep 500.
   Gov. Steve Cowper set the period of silence to mark the 30-day
anniversary of the grounding of the Exxon Valdez. The fully loaded
tanker struck a reef and spilled 10.1 million gallons of crude into
wildlife-rich Prince William Sound.
   In Cordova, a fishing community 40 miles from the accident,
organizers planned an afternoon of activities, including speeches,
displays of photographs and a children's mural depicting the
America's worst oil spill.
   ``We wanted the world to know how much we loved Prince William
Sound, how beautiful we think it is,'' said Belle Mickelson, who
coordinates commercial fisheries education programs at Cordova High
School.
   ``Maybe people will understand why we're so sad. ... Seeing
whales three feet away ... bears and fish swimming upstream'' are
experiences threatened by the spill, she said.
   Many fisherman have expressed frustration with Exxon and the
Coast Guard over the lack of progress since the March 24 accident.
They have been scooping oil with buckets.
   A makeshift fleet of 48 skimmer boats returned to their work
shortly after daylight Saturday. The oil is being taken to one of
five barges hired by Exxon to receive the recovered oil, which will
be reprocessed by the company.
   Low clouds and fog grounded observation and supply planes early
Saturday.
   The cleanup concentrated on sites where seals haul themselves
out of the water.
   Exxon spokesman Joe Tucker said 303,000 feet of boom had been
deployed to keep the 14 percent of the spill still at sea from
coating beaches.
   Less than a half-mile of beaches have been cleaned, while the
spill has touched beaches along more than 300 miles of the Kenai
Peninsula and Kodiak Island, the latter home to many brown bears
and the world's No. 1 fishing port.
   Robbins said that by midday Saturday the 425-foot Soviet skimmer
Vaidogubsky picked up about 10,000 gallons of oil at Gore Point,
the site of large pools of oil trapped by spectacular rock
outcroppings.
   The vessel arrived Wednesday but spent days testing its booms
and refueling. As of Saturday morning it had yet to scoop up any
oil.
   Alaska policymakers worried that the state's image has been at
least as sullied as the spectacular shoreline. Sen. Ted Stevens
called on Exxon to pay for a program to inspect Alsaska seafood and
certify its purity to ease consumer fears.
   ``There's indications of a fall-off in demand for Alaska
products,'' the Republican said. ``It's the largest problem I've
seen so far, and it could be overwhelming if not addressed.''
   Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, and Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., toured
oil-tainted shores with Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr. and
said Friday they will introduce legislation to make one person _
probably the Coast Guard commandant _ responsible for spill
cleanups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
