<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Kirkwood     04-22 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Kirkwood,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coauthor of Book For `Chorus Line' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prize-winning playwright and novelist James
Kirkwood, who co-wrote the book for the record-setting Broadway
musical ``A Chorus Line,'' has died of cancer.
   Kirkwood, who lived in Key West, Fla., died Friday in New York,
where he was hospitalized recently, said a friend, Arthur
Beckenstein.
   Although Kirkwood's age was listed as 58, he recently said he
was actually 64. ``As an actor, I got in the habit of lying about
my age,'' he said.
   In 1976, Kirkwood won a Tony Award and a Pulitzer Prize for ``A
Chorus Line,'' written with Nicholas Dante.
   ``A Chorus Line,'' which also won a Drama Critics Circle Award,
opened in 1975, logged its record 3,389th performance in 1983 and
remains the longest-running musical in Broadway history.
   Kirkwood also wrote plays including ``Unhealthy to Be
Unpleasant,'' produced on Broadway in 1966, and ``Legends,'' which
toured the country in 1986 and 1987 with Mary Martin and Carol
Channing.
   His books included ``P.S. Your Cat Is Dead!'' which he adapted
for the stage, and ``American Grotesque,'' a nonfiction work about
a conspiracy in the aftermath of the assassination of President
Kennedy.
   Shortly before he died, Kirkwood finished a book about his own
experiences called ``Diary of a Mad Playwright.''
   Kirkwood followed his actor-parents, Lila Lee and James Kirkwood
Sr., into show business at 14. He appeared in shows including
``Wonderful Town'' and ``Welcome Darlings'' and his motion picture
credits included ``Mommie Dearest'' and ``The Supernaturals.'' He
also served in the U.S. Coast Guard for three years.
   Kirkwood also was part of a comedy-satire team called Jim
Kirkwood and Lee Goodman, which performed in nightclubs around the
country and also had a radio show on WOR for several years.
   He is survived by a half-brother and a half-sister. A memorial
service is planned.
</TEXT>
