<FIRST>r i AM-EEC-Agriculture     04-22 0127</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-Agriculture,0130</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Freezes Farm Prices For Another Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture ministers in the European Economic
Community agreed Saturday to freeze most farm prices within its 12
nations to keep the farm budget at $33 billion.
   After a weeklong debate, the 12 EEC ministers agreed to keep
price supports generally at last year's levels. The biggest cut
will be made in guarantees to growers of citrus fruits, down 7.5
percent. Prices for sugar will drop by 2 percent, although the
community's executive commission had requested a 5 percent cut.
   A tax on the production of surplus milk will be reduced by 25
percent, a move that milk producers had supported.
   The EEC farm budget is more than 60 percent of the
organization's total budget.
