<FIRST>r a AM-MonumentFire     04-22 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monument Fire,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters Contain Most Of Brush Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONUMENT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 firefighters contained most of
a brush fire Saturday that forced the evacuation of 200 homes when
it erupted the day before.
   Firefighters hampered by rough terrain completed 3{ miles, or 70
percent, of the five miles of fire line needed to contain the
blaze, said Dennis Neill, a fire information officer with the U.S.
Forest Service.
   No further evacuations were expected. ``We still have some
concerns about some of the subdivisions in the immediate area of
the fire,'' Neill said.
   The blaze flared up southwest of Monument around noon Friday. By
midafternoon, it could be seen miles away as it consumed grass,
scrub oak and ponderosa pine on private land and land in the Pike
National Forest about 20 miles north of Colorado Springs.
   Authorities ordered the evacuation of four subdivisions
containing 200 homes, but allowed people back into their homes
Friday night.
   The fire's cause was unknown, Neill said.
   ``This is an early fire for us,'' he said. ``It's a symptom of
the dry weather we've had for the last several years. We don't
normally expect these conditions until maybe June or July.''
   Higher-than-expected humidity and low winds helped firefighters
Saturday, Neill said.
