<SECOND>AM-Black Student-Protest,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wayne State Asks Students To End Building Occupation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne State University officials called for an
end Saturday to the 10-day occupation of a campus building by
students protesting the school's treatment of blacks.
   The students conducting a so-called ``study-in'' at the Helen
Newberry Joy Student Services Center did not respond to the
request, which was the first made by the university, said Wayne
State spokesman Vernon Foss. Later that night, school officials met
with the students.
   As many as 100 students initially occupied the building April
12, but only 40 or 50 were there Saturday night, said a campus
policeman who refused to give his name.
   Foss said the request was part of what the university called its
``last, best offer'' in several days of negotiations with the
students.
   The proposal included an offer of amnesty that would stay in
effect until Saturday night's session was concluded. University
officials, however, had no plans to ask campus or Detroit police to
remove the students, Foss said.
   The university has agreed to 13 of the students' 17 demands,
including granting department status to the Center for Black
Studies. Administators said they would ask the Board of Governors
to establish the department by September.
   Saturday night's meeting was held to address the four unresolved
demands: increased recruitment of black students, reinstatement of
money cut from the black studies center's budget over the past 10
years, increased financial aid for blacks and more black faculty.
   The occupied building contains offices that handle financial
aid, registration, student records and other student services.
