<FIRST>u i AM-FossilHoax     04-22 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fossil Hoax,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Australian Scientist Claims To Expose Major Fossil Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Panjab is cq in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Australian scientist has charged an
influential Indian scholar faked the fossil history of India and
the Himalayas in what he called one of biggest paleontological
frauds of all time.
   ``It's a massive fabric of disinformation liberally poured into
a 25-year period without anyone blowing the whistle,'' said John
Talent, an associate professor in earth sciences at Sydney's
Macquarie University.
   Talent accused prominent Indian geologist Viswa Jit Gupta of
building his career on a ``warped, twisted, tangled'' web of
disinformation.
   Gupta, a geologist at the Panjab University in Chandigarh,
India, was quoted in The New York Times Sunday as saying Talent was
lying about him. He said Talent's charges were ``far from the
truth'' and the product of ``malicious bias and professional
jealousy.''
   Talent, in an interview Thursday with The Associated Press, said
Gupta had invented fictitious fossils and had rewritten the
geological history of northern India. He said Gupta based his
writings on specimens ``that could be bought in fossil shops, and
were often picked up in the United States, parts of Europe, China
and elsewhere.''
   He said Gupta had reported discovering a ``huge number'' of
fossils in remote areas of the Himalayas, which because of the high
mountain range is accessible to few scientists.
   He contended that most of the specimens were ``common laboratory
rocks.''
   Talent's findings were published Thursday in the respected
British journal Nature.
   Talent said Gupta had published about 400 scientific papers and
several major texts on the geology of the Indian Subcontinent.
   He said academics from around the world had collaborated on the
papers, which were readily accepted by leading international
journals.
   The Sydney Morning Herald newspaper, in an earlier interview,
said Talent estimated that about 60 scientists had ``unwittingly
been drawn into the fraud by agreeing to examine specimens and
co-author papers.''
   Talent said he first became suspicious of Gupta's research in
1971 because of a research paper on tiny marine fossils called
graptolites, which he reported came from a site in Kashmir.
   After visiting the site, Talent said, he discovered ``to my
amazement, you could never find graptolites or any kind of fossils
there because the site was so mashed up.''
   ``I became intrigued at the results that Gupta was putting into
the literature,'' he said. ``I intially believed that the fraud
would collapse under its own weight.
   ``It reached a point that there was so much misinformation that
it was getting difficult to place our own work and that of our
colleagues in context.''
   Gupta told the Times he had invited Talent to visit his
laboratory in Chandigarh and the fossil sites that were in dispute,
but Talent declined. Talent told the newspaper he had not been able
to fit such visits into his schedule, and was calling for an
investigation by a panel of scientists.
</TEXT>
