<FIRST>r a AM-AnimalResearch     04-22 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Animal Research,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critically Ill Activists Rally In Support Medical Tests On Animals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 people, including seriously ill
patients who said medical research with animals had saved their
lives, rallied Saturday at Northwestern University in support of
such research.
   The rally by students, faculty members and pro-research
demonstrators came after a rash of protests and death threats
against biomedical researchers at the university in this suburb
north of Chicago.
   University President Arnold Weber told demonstrators the
university would not be intimidated by recent acts of vandalism
against university buildings, including spray-painted death threats
against faculty members.
   Animal rights groups have denied any connection with the threats
and vandalism.
   Seriously ill demonstrators said research using animals is their
only only hope for a cure, and claimed that foes are jeopardizing
medical progress.
   ``We need to look at the human side of it, and realize what
would happen if animal rights activists got their way,'' said Steve
Carroll, national executive director of the Incurably Ill for
Animal Research, a group he said has 2,500 members nationwide.
   Carroll, 37, was severely burned over 50 percent of his body in
an airplane accident and suffers from chronic osteomyelitis, a
painful bone infection he said can be treated thanks to tests on
animals.
   ``I am a person whose life was saved by animal research,'' he
said. ``There's no way I can express how grateful I am this
research was done.
   ``Painkillers that allowed me to keep my sanity were developed
on animals,'' Carroll said. ``We wouldn't have coronary bypass
surgery, be able to remove cateracts, or have joint implants for
arthritis victims'' without the research.
   Carroll was joined by about a dozen other patients who have
illnesses for which there is not yet a cure, including diabetics,
cancer survivors and two children with congenital heart defects.
   Two parents also spoke at the rally, contending that their
children would not be alive if it weren't for medical progress made
through animal testing.
   A member of Concerned Citizens for Ethical Research, a group
opposed to animal testing, said he was outraged by what he called a
distortion of the issue.
   ``They paint a picture trying to say that animal rights
activists are hurting medical progress,'' said Steve Davis. ``Just
because something has been done in the past, or is legal, doesn't
mean that it's right.''
   The Concerned Citizens group has targeted five scientists in
recent weeks, pressuring them to discontinue their research.
   The group contends Northwestern researchers starve monkeys and
stick electrodes and needles in cats' eyes. Researchers counter
that the animals are anesthetized and feel no pain.
</TEXT>
