<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Northwest     04-22 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Pilots Urged to Settle to Attract `Friendly' Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friendly investors could help Northwest
Airlines defend itself from a hostile takeover bid if the carrier's
5,000 pilots quickly agree to a contract, according to a management
letter made public Friday.
   ``Frankly, there are alternatives available to us from friendly
investors,'' Chairman Steven Rothmeier said in the letter, which
was sent to pilots of the nation's fourth-largest airline on
Thursday.
   ``The absence of a pilot contract keeps the patient money
away,'' the letter said. ``But it does nothing to scare away the
highly leveraged money from those investors who don't really care
because if they can't make the airline work, they just break it
up.''
   The letter was released to the media after stock in Northwest
parent NWA Inc. closed at $102.50 on the New York Stock Exchange,
up $3.75 from Thursday's close.
   The stock price reflects a belief on Wall Street that there will
be a bid higher than billionaire Marvin Davis' current $2.7
billion, or $90-a-share, hostile tender offer.
   Calls to the Twin Cities headquarters of the Air Line Pilots
Association went unanswered Friday night. Pilots have been working
under two separate contracts since Northwest acquired Republic
Airlines in the fall of 1986. One of the key sticking points in
negotiations is merging the airlines' seniority lists. Both
contracts have expired.
   ``We are prepared and willing to negotiate around the clock to
reach an agreement,'' Rothmeier wrote. ``We are in a fluid
situation that can change, quite literally, from hour to hour.''
   According to testimony in a lawsuit filed by Northwest against
Davis, representatives for Davis have been in contact with labor
leaders at Northwest, including the pilots union. A judge has
issued a temporary restraining order prohibiting Davis from
``disrupting'' the contract talks, but the order does not forbid
``nondisruptive'' communication.
   Davis aides have said they want to establish an ``open
dialogue'' with the pilots. Davis himself has said he does not
intend to break up the airline by selling strategic assets to pay
takeover debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
