<DOCNO> AP890422-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 0237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-OracleofOmaha Adv24   04-22 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Oracle of Omaha, Adv 24,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, April 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Warren Buffett's Annual Meeting: Exalted Wizard Holds Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Annual Meeting Season</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many company bosses duck investor salvos at annual meetings, but
Warren Buffett likely will bask in shareholder adulation because
he's enriched them for the 24th year.
   Buffett, one of the world's wealthiest people, is chairman of
Berkshire Hathaway Inc., a $6 billion conglomerate with interests
that include an encyclopedia, a homespun candy maker, an Omaha
furniture mart, a giant insurance company and investments in Coca
Cola Co., Capital Cities ABC Inc., the Washington Post Co. and
Salomon Brothers Inc., among others.
   Folksy, charming and unconventional, the 57-year-old investor
wows shareholders and stock analysts with a pithy annual report he
writes himself, filled with insights into what he considers good
and bad in his business and the economy in general.
   It's earned him the nickname, ``Oracle of Omaha.''
   This year, Buffett began the report with a 21-page letter to
shareholders, telling them the stock market is lousy, corporate
taxes are higher and the takeover business is getting expensive.
   Nonetheless, he wrote, Berkshire's management team gained $569
million in net worth for them in 1988, contributing to an average
net worth gain of 23 percent over the last 24 years. He also
proclaimed Berkshire had made a great investment in Borsheim's, a
flourishing Omaha jewelry business.
   ``We continue to concentrate our investments in a very few
companies that we try to understand well,'' Buffett wrote. ``There
are only a handful of businesses about which we have strong
long-term convictions. Therefore, when we find such a business, we
want to participate in a meaningful way. We agree with Mae West:
`Too much of a good thing can be wonderful.'''
   Buffett's report is a prelude to Berkshire Hathaway's annual
meeting, which he's holding Monday in Omaha, the company's
headquarters. He plans to make shareholders feel like they're at a
family reunion.
   ``After the meeting we will have several buses available to take
you to visit Mrs. B at the Nebraska Furniture Mart and Ike Friedman
at Borsheim's,'' Buffett wrote to the shareholders. ``Be prepared
for bargains.''
   The biggest bargain Berkshire Hathaway shareholders ever got was
buying the company's stock, which had a book value of about $20 a
share in the mid 1960s, when Buffett acquired what was then
Massachusetts cloth milling concern with $10 million in assets. Now
its book value is nearly $3,000 a share and it trades on the New
York Stock Exchange at nearly $5,900 a share.
   Berkshire Hathaway is considered such a gem that takeover
strategist T. Boone Pickens ranked it last month as among the top
20 of 1,000 big companies for what he called its commitment to
shareholders.
   Buffett's annual report is so widely followed that USA Today
said recently it ``runs a good chance of being the only one anyone
actually reads on or off Wall Street.''
   Verne McKenzie, Berkshire Hathaway's chief financial officer,
said the company is besieged with requests for the annual report
and shareholders flock like pilgrims to the annual meeting.
   ``People travel here from the far reaches of the country and the
world,'' he said.
   Richard A. Lewis, chairman of Corporate Annual Reports Inc., a
professional annual report publishing concern, gave high marks to
Buffett's yearly prognostications to shareholders, largely because
it showed he was honest and direct with fellow owners of the
company.
   ``Buffett is one of the four or five richest men in America,''
Lewis said. ``When he speaks, people listen. He uses his report to
say what he wants to say. He uses the report to underscore his own
investment principles and the keys to his success.''
   Nonetheless, Buffett is not universally admired. Sid Cato,
publisher of a monthly newsletter on annual reports based in
Waukesha, Wis., ranked Berkshire Hathaway's as one of the 10 worst
last year, largely because of what he called Buffett's inflated ego.
   ``I wrote, `Mr. Buffett, you're starting to get on my nerves
already, enough already,'' Cato said.
   Asked if he'd seen this year's annual report, Cato said, ``No,
he has not seen fit to send me a copy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Monday, April 24</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
