<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions April 22-23</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED:Monday's trading.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures advanced for the second consecutive
week on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in May settled Friday at $4.14{ a bushel, up
from $4.12} a week earlier; May corn rose to $2.75\ a bushel from
$2.70}; May oats rallied to $2.02{ a bushel from $1.91}; and May
soybeans rose to $7.60 a bushel from $7.33.
   Live cattle futures prices rose but other livestock and meat
futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   June live cattle rose to 71.42 cents a pound from 71.10 cents;
May feeder cattle dipped to 76.17 cents a pound from 76.27 cents;
June hogs slipped to 45.60 cents a pound from 46.22 cents; July
frozen pork bellies dropped to 31.30 cents a pound from 33.30 cents.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell slightly on New York's
Commodity Exchange.
   June gold dropped to $388.20 a troy ounce from $389.80; May
silver fell to $5.765 a troy ounce from $5.825.
   Energy futures rose sharply for the second straight week on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for delivery in June settled
Friday at $21.32 a barrel compared with $19.86 the previous week;
May heating oil rose to 53.63 cents a gallon from 52.91 cents; May
unleaded gasoline went to 74.16 cents a gallon from 70.02 cents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for weekend editions April 22-23</NOTE>
